rl-status=live}}</ref>\n| Oh Boy Records\n|-\n| 2019\n! scope=\"row\"| ''My Old Kentucky Home, Goodnight''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l0EiV423j0M|title=John Prine \u2013 My Old Kentucky Home, Goodnight|publisher=[[Oh Boy Records]]|accessdate=June 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190520183559/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l0EiV423j0M|archive-date=May 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| Oh Boy Records\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links|d=Q520296|c=Category:John Prine|q=John Prine|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|wikt=no|s=no|species=no}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.johnprine.com}}\n* {{Discogs artist}}\n* {{IMDb name|0697789}}\n* {{twitter|JohnPrineMusic}}\n* {{instagram|john_prine}}\n* {{facebook|JohnPrine}}\n* [https://open.spotify.com/artist/0nJUwPwC9Ti4vvuJ0q3MfT John Prine] on [[Spotify]]\n* [https://www.loc.gov/today/cyberlc/feature_wdesc.php?rec=3677 ''A Literary Evening with John Prine and Ted Kooser.'' March 9, 2005. The Poetry and Literature Center at the Library of Congress.]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-ach|aw}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Billy Joe Shaver]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Americana Music Association|AMA Lifetime Achievement Award for Songwriting]]|years=2003}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Jack Clement|Cowboy Jack Clement]]}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Loretta Lynn]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Americana Music Association|AMA Artist of the Year]]|years=2005}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Neil Young]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{John Prine|state=expanded}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Prine, John}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:American folk singers]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American country singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:United States Army soldiers]]\n[[Category:American country guitarists]]\n[[Category:American bluegrass guitarists]]\n[[Category:American acoustic guitarists]]\n[[Category:American folk guitarists]]\n[[Category:Cancer survivors]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Folk musicians from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Mail carriers]]\n[[Category:Old Town School of Folk musicians]]\n[[Category:People from Maywood, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Illinois]]\n[[Category:20th-century American guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Country musicians from Illinois]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American country singer-songwriter}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = John Prine\n| image = John Prine by Ron Baker.jpg\n| image_size =\n| caption = Prine in 2006\n| landscape = yes\n| background = solo_singer\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1946|10|10}}\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|2020|04|07|1946|10|10}}\n| birth_place = [[Maywood, Illinois]], U.S.\n| death_place = [[Nashville, Tennessee]], U.S.\n| instrument = {{Unbulleted list|[[Vocals]]|[[Guitar]]}}\n| genre = [[Country folk]], [[Bluegrass music|bluegrass]], [[Americana (music)|Americana]]\n| occupation ={{hlist|[[Singer-songwriter]]|[[guitarist]]}}\n| years_active = 1969\u20132020\n| label = {{hlist|[[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]|[[Asylum Records|Asylum]]|[[Oh Boy Records|Oh Boy]]|[[Rhino Records|Rhino]]}}\n| associated_acts = {{Unbulleted list|[[Steve Goodman]]|[[Iris DeMent]]}} <!-- and many other artists too numerous to list here. -->\n| website = {{URL|johnprine.net|JohnPrine.net}}\n}}\n\n'''John Prine''' (October 10, 1946&nbsp;\u2013 April 7, 2020) was an American [[country folk]] [[singer-songwriter]]. He was active as a composer, recording artist, and live performer from the early 1970s until his death and was known for an often humorous style of original music that has elements of [[protest music|protest]] and social commentary.\n\nBorn and raised in [[Maywood, Illinois]], Prine learned to play the guitar at the age of 14. He attended classes at Chicago's [[Old Town School of Folk Music]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/oldtownschool/status/989572224213450752 |title=John Prine OTSFM Registration Card |publisher=Old Town School of Folk Music |date=September 17, 1964 |accessdate=April 26, 2018}}</ref> After serving in [[West Germany]] with the U.S. Army, he returned to [[Chicago]] in the late 1960s, where he worked as a mailman, writing and singing songs as a hobby.\n\nA member of Chicago's [[folk revival]], he was discovered by [[Kris Kristofferson]] (although Prine himself credited film critic [[Roger Ebert]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ultimateclassicrock.com/john-prine-roger-ebert-first-review/|title=How an Unplanned Roger Ebert Review Launched John Prine's Career|last=Wilkening|first=Matthew|website=Ultimate Classic Rock|language=en|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>), resulting in the production of Prine's [[John Prine (album)|self-titled debut album]] with [[Atlantic Records]] in 1971. The acclaim earned by this LP led Prine to focus on his musical career, and he recorded three more albums for Atlantic. He then signed to [[Asylum Records]], where he recorded an additional three albums. In 1984 he co-founded [[Oh Boy Records]], an independent record label with which he would release most of his subsequent albums. After his battle with [[Squamous cell carcinoma|squamous cell cancer]] in 1998, Prine's vocals deepened into a gravelly voice. Prine died on April 7, 2020, of complications resulting from [[COVID-19]].\n\nWidely cited as one of the most influential songwriters of his generation, Prine was known for humorous lyrics about love, life, and current events, as well as serious songs with social commentary and songs that recollect melancholy tales from his life. In 2020, he received the [[Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award]].\n\n==Early life==\nPrine was the son of William Mason Prine, a [[Tool and die maker|tool-and-die]] maker, and Verna Valentine (Hamm), a homemaker, both from [[Muhlenberg County, Kentucky|Muhlenberg County]], [[Kentucky]]. He was born and raised in the Maywood suburb of Chicago.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|last=Barry|first=Dan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/10/arts/music/john-prine-endures-with-a-half-smile-and-a-song.html|title=John Prine Endures, With a Half-Smile and a Song|date=April 6, 2016|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=March 30, 2020|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330175317/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/10/arts/music/john-prine-endures-with-a-half-smile-and-a-song.html|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=zcAvBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA76&lpg=PA76&dq=%22William+Mason+Prine%22&source=bl&ots=jDOm_3v6oV&sig=ACfU3U35TPsyQSJTsNvdrVEMe6ixKUIQpQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjkg93TiNjoAhUMmuAKHXncA00Q6AEwA3oECAkQAQ|title=John Prine: In Spite of Himself|first=Eddie|last=Huffman|date=March 15, 2015|page=76|publisher=[[University of Texas Press]]|via=Google Books}}</ref> He started playing guitar at age 14, taught by his brother, David.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.shrout.co.uk/jpbackpage.html |title=John Prine Information |website=Shrout.co.uk |date=October 10, 1946 |accessdate=March 15, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006062927/http://www.shrout.co.uk/jpbackpage.html |archive-date=October 6, 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> He attended classes at Chicago's [[Old Town School of Folk Music]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/oldtownschool/status/98957222421345075 |title=John Prine OTSFM Registration Card |publisher=Old Town School of Folk Music |date=September 17, 1964 |accessdate=April 26, 2018}}</ref> and [[Proviso East High School|Proviso Township High School]] (later called Proviso East) in [[Maywood, Illinois]]. He was a mailman for five years and was drafted into the [[United States Army]] during the [[Vietnam War]] era, serving in Germany, before beginning his musical career in [[Chicago]].<ref>{{cite news |title=John Prine, Grammy-winning singer-songwriter, dead at 73 from coronavirus complications |url=https://nypost.com/2020/04/07/john-prine-grammy-winning-singer-songwriter-dead-at-73-from-coronavirus/ |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |newspaper=[[New York Post]] |date=April 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408023213/https://nypost.com/2020/04/07/john-prine-grammy-winning-singer-songwriter-dead-at-73-from-coronavirus/ |archive-date=April 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn the late 1960s, while Prine was delivering mail, he began to sing at [[open mic]] evenings at the Fifth Peg on Armitage Avenue in Chicago. Prine was initially a spectator, reluctant to perform, but eventually did so in response to a \"You think you can do better?\" comment made to him by another performer.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Kot |first=Greg |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2010-02-28-ct-ae-0228-john-prine-20100228-story.html |title=John Prine recalls his Chicago folk roots |date=February 28, 2010 |work=Chicago Tribune |access-date=April 8, 2020 |language=en-US}}</ref> ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' movie critic [[Roger Ebert]] heard him there by chance and wrote the first review Prine ever received, calling him a great songwriter.<ref name=ebert/>{{quote|He appears on stage with such modesty he almost seems to be backing into the spotlight. He sings rather quietly, and his guitar work is good, but he doesn't show off. He starts slow. But after a song or two, even the drunks in the room begin to listen to his lyrics. And then he has you.<ref name=ebert>{{cite news |url=http://www.rogerebert.com/balder-and-dash/john-prine-american-legend |title=Roger Ebert's Journal: \"John Prine: American Legend\" |work=Chicago Sun-Times |accessdate=February 23, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150223213137/http://www.rogerebert.com/balder-and-dash/john-prine-american-legend |archive-date=February 23, 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>}} Prine became a central figure in the Chicago [[American folk music revival|folk revival]], which also included such singer-songwriters as [[Steve Goodman]], [[Michael Peter Smith]], [[Bonnie Koloc]], [[Jim Post]], [[Tom Dundee]], [[Anne Hills]] and [[Fred Holstein]]. Joined by such established musicians as [[Jethro Burns]] and [[Bob Gibson (musician)|Bob Gibson]], Prine performed frequently at a variety of Chicago clubs.<ref>{{cite web |title=John Prine obituary |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/08/john-prine-obituary |website=www.theguardian.com |publisher=The Guardian |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n=== 1970s ===\nIn 1971, Prine's [[John Prine (album)|self-titled debut album]] was released. He and friend Steve Goodman had each been active in the [[Chicago]] folk scene before being \"discovered\" by [[Kris Kristofferson]] (Kristofferson remarked that Prine wrote songs so good that \"we'll have to break his thumbs\").<ref name=\"Chilton, Martin 2013\">Chilton, Martin. \"John Prine: I Find the Human Condition Funny; John Prine, One of Bob Dylan's Favourite Songwriters, Is Appearing in the UK and Ireland. Here He Talks to Martin Chilton.\" Daily Telegraph [London, England] February 8, 2013, Web Edition Articles ed.: Print.</ref> The album included his signature songs \"Illegal Smile\", \"[[Sam Stone (song)|Sam Stone]]\", and the folk and country standards \"[[Angel from Montgomery]]\" and \"[[Paradise (John Prine song)|Paradise]].\" The album also featured \"Hello in There\", a song about aging that was later covered by numerous artists, and \"Far From Me\", a lonely waltz about lost love for a waitress that Prine later said was his favorite of all his songs. The album received many positive reviews, and some hailed Prine as \"the next Dylan.\" [[Bob Dylan]] himself appeared unannounced at one of Prine's first [[New York City]] club appearances, anonymously backing him on harmonica.<ref name=\"Huffman\">{{cite book |last1=Huffman |first1=Eddie |title=John Prine: In Spite of Himself |date=2015 |publisher=[[University of Texas Press]] |isbn=9780292748224 |pages=69-70 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zcAvBgAAQBAJ |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |quote=''Rolling Stone'' caught up with Prine in New York shortly before the album's release [referring to ''Diamonds in the Rough'']. The opening paragraph of Ed McCormack's story described Prine on stage at the Bitter End, halfway through a six-night stand, calling out for a special guest: 'Whar's that harmonica player?' The 'nervously nondescript figure' who joined him was none other than Bob Dylan.}}</ref>\n\nPrine's second album, ''[[Diamonds in the Rough (album)|Diamonds in the Rough]]'' (1972), was a surprise for many after the critical success of his first LP; it was an uncommercial, stripped-down affair that reflected Prine's fondness for bluegrass music and features songs reminiscent of [[Hank Williams]]. Highlights include the allegorical \"[[The Great Compromise (song)|The Great Compromise]]\", which includes a recitation and addresses the [[Vietnam War]], and the ballad \"Souvenirs\", which Prine later recorded with Goodman.<ref>{{cite web |title=Looking Back on John Prine Buddy Steve Goodman |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/looking-back-on-john-prine-buddy-steve-goodman-860284/ |website=www.rollingstone.com |publisher=Rollingstone |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSubsequent albums include ''[[Sweet Revenge (John Prine album)|Sweet Revenge]]'' (1973), containing such fan favorites as \"Dear Abby\", \"Grandpa Was a Carpenter\", and \"Christmas in Prison\", and [[Common Sense (John Prine album)|''Common Sense'']] (1975), with \"Come Back to Us Barbara Lewis Hare Krishna Beauregard\". The latter album was Prine's first to be charted in the US Top 100 by ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', reflecting growing commercial success. It was produced by Steve Cropper. 1978's ''[[Bruised Orange]]'' was a Steve Goodman-produced album that gave listeners songs such as \"That's The Way That The World Goes 'Round\", \"Sabu Visits the Twin Cities Alone\", \"Fish and Whistle\", and the title track.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cocks |first1=Jay |title=Bruised Orange |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/bruised-orange-190100/ |website=www.rollingstone.com |publisher=Rolling Stone |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1974, singer [[David Allan Coe]] achieved considerable success on the country charts with \"[[You Never Even Called Me by My Name]]\", co-written by Prine and Goodman. The song good-naturedly spoofs stereotypical country music lyrics. Prine refused to take a songwriter's credit and the tune went to Goodman, although Goodman bought Prine a jukebox as a gift from his publishing royalties.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OMiLqHTvbKE|title=John Prine \u2013 You Never Even Call Me by My Name (1987)|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=October 4, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228063135/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OMiLqHTvbKE&gl=US&hl=en&has_verified=1&bpctr=9999999999|archive-date=February 28, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1975, Prine toured the U.S. and Canada with a full band featuring guitarist [[Arlen Roth]].<ref>{{cite web |title=About Arlen Roth |url=https://www.arlenroth.com/about |website=www.arlenroth.com |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe 1979 album ''[[Pink Cadillac (album)|Pink Cadillac]]'' features two songs produced by [[Sun Records]] founder [[Sam Phillips]], who by this time rarely did any studio work. The song \"Saigon\" is about a Vietnam vet traumatized by the war (\"The static in my attic's gettin' ready to blow\"). During the recording, one of the guitar amps blew up (which is evident on the album).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ramsey |first1=Jan |title=John Prine |url=http://www.offbeat.com/articles/john-prine/ |website=offbeat.com |publisher=Offbeat Magazine |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> The other song Phillips produced is \"How Lucky\", about Prine's hometown.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Betts |first1=Stephen |title=Hear John Prine Update His \u2018Song of Personal Confrontation\u2019 \u2018How Lucky\u2019 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/john-prine-how-lucky-amazon-music-723667/ |website=www.rollingstone.com |publisher=Rolling Stone |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 1980s ===\nIn 1981, rejecting the established model of the recording industry, which Prine felt exploited singers and songwriters, he co-founded the independent record label [[Oh Boy Records]] in [[Nashville, Tennessee]]. His fans, supporting the project, sent him enough money to cover the costs, in advance, of his next album.<ref name=\":0\" /> Prine continued writing and recording albums throughout the 1980s. His songs continued to be covered by other artists; the country supergroup [[The Highwaymen (country supergroup)|The Highwaymen]] recorded \"The 20th Century Is Almost Over\", which had been written by Prine and Goodman. Steve Goodman died of leukemia in 1984 and Prine contributed four tracks to ''A Tribute to Steve Goodman'', including a cover version of Goodman's \"My Old Man\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Oermann|first=Robert K.|title=Sade's 'Promise' broken; Grace's is the 'Greatest'|newspaper=The Tennesseean|date=January 12, 1986}}</ref>\n\n=== 1990s ===\nIn 1991, Prine released the [[Grammy Award]]-winning ''The Missing Years'', his first collaboration with producer and [[Tom Petty and the Heartbreakers|Heartbreakers]] bassist [[Howie Epstein]]. The title song records Prine's humorous take on what [[Jesus]] did in the unrecorded years between his childhood and [[Ministry of Jesus|ministry]].<ref name=\"Rolling Stone Milward\">{{cite news |last1=Milward |first1=John |title=The Missing Years |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/the-missing-years-92682/ |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |work=Rolling Stone |date=January 23, 1992 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408035952/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/the-missing-years-92682/ |archive-date=April 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"LA Times Davis\">{{cite news |last1=Davis |first1=Noel |title=Finding Success in \u2018Missing Years\u2019 : Pop music: John Prine, who will perform at the Coach House, says the popularity of his latest album caught him by surprise. |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1992-07-07-ca-1761-story.html |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=July 7, 1992 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408035952/https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1992-07-07-ca-1761-story.html |archive-date=April 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Elsewhere Reid\">{{cite web |last1=Reid |first1=Graham |title=John Prine: The Missing Years (1991) |url=https://www.elsewhere.co.nz/essentialelsewhere/2043/john-prine-the-missing-years-1991/ |website=Elsewhere |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |date=March 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408040505/https://www.elsewhere.co.nz/essentialelsewhere/2043/john-prine-the-missing-years-1991/ |archive-date=April 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 1995, ''[[Lost Dogs and Mixed Blessings]]'' was released, another collaboration with Epstein.<ref name=\"Rolling Stone Manning\">{{cite news |last1=Manning |first1=Kara |title=John Prine: \u2018It\u2019s Hard to Write a Happy Love Song\u2019 |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/john-prine-lost-dogs-mixed-blessings-album-interview-1995-191626/ |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |work=Rolling Stone |date=September 21, 1995 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408041204/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/john-prine-lost-dogs-mixed-blessings-album-interview-1995-191626/ |archive-date=April 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Prine followed in 1999 with ''[[In Spite of Ourselves]]'', which was unusual for him in that it contained only one original song (the title track); the rest were covers of classic country songs. All of the tracks are duets with well-known female country vocalists, including [[Lucinda Williams]], [[Emmylou Harris]], [[Patty Loveless]], [[Dolores Keane]], [[Trisha Yearwood]], and [[Iris DeMent]].<ref name=\"AV Club Klein\">{{cite news |last1=Klein |first1=Joshua |title=John Prine: In Spite Of Ourselves |url=https://music.avclub.com/john-prine-in-spite-of-ourselves-1798193623 |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |work=AV Club |date=March 29, 2002 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191106102513/https://music.avclub.com/john-prine-in-spite-of-ourselves-1798193623 |archive-date=November 6, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Modern Vinyl Spacek\">{{cite web |last1=Spacek |first1=Nick |title=Vinyl Review: John Prine \u2014 In Spite of Ourselves |url=http://modern-vinyl.com/2016/09/19/vinyl-review-john-prine-in-spite-of-ourselves/ |website=Modern Vinyl |accessdate=April 7, 2020 |date=September 19, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408042004/http://modern-vinyl.com/2016/09/19/vinyl-review-john-prine-in-spite-of-ourselves/ |archive-date=April 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== 2000s ===\nIn 2001, Prine appeared in a supporting role in the [[Billy Bob Thornton]] movie ''[[Daddy & Them]]''. \"In Spite of Ourselves\" is played during the end credits.<ref>{{cite web |title=Daddy and Them (2001) |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/daddy_and_them |website=rottentomatoes.com |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nPrine recorded a version of [[Stephen Foster]]'s \"[[My Old Kentucky Home]]\" in 2004 for the compilation album ''[[Beautiful Dreamer (album)|Beautiful Dreamer]]'', which won the Grammy for Best Traditional Folk Album in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |title=47th Annual GRAMMY Awards (2004) |url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards/47th-annual-grammy-awards-2004 |website=www.grammy.com |publisher=Grammy.com |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Prine released his first all-new offering since ''Lost Dogs and Mixed Blessings'', the album ''[[Fair & Square]]'', which tended toward a more laid-back, acoustic approach. The album contains songs such as \"Safety Joe\", about a man who has never taken any risks in his life, and also \"Some Humans Ain't Human\", Prine's protest piece on the album, which talks about the ugly side of [[human nature]] and includes a quick shot at President [[George W. Bush]]. ''Fair & Square'' won the 2005 Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Folk Album. The album contains original songs plus two covers: [[A.P. Carter]]'s \"Bear Creek Blues\" and [[Blaze Foley]]'s \"Clay Pigeons\".<ref>{{cite web |title=48th Annual GRAMMY Awards (2005) |url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards/48th-annual-grammy-awards |website=www.grammy.com |publisher=Grammy.com |accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== 2010s ===\nOn June 22, 2010, Oh Boy Records released a tribute album titled ''[[Broken Hearts and Dirty Windows: The Songs of John Prine]]''. The album features members of the modern folk revival including [[My Morning Jacket]], [[The Avett Brothers]], [[Conor Oberst and the Mystic Valley Band]], [[Old Crow Medicine Show]], [[Lambchop (band)|Lambchop]], [[Josh Ritter]], [[Drive-By Truckers]], [[Nickel Creek]]'s [[Sara Watkins]], [[Deer Tick (band)|Deer Tick]] featuring Liz Isenberg, [[Justin Townes Earle]], [[Those Darlins]], and [[Bon Iver]]'s [[Justin Vernon]].<ref name=\"broken hearts\">{{cite web |url=http://brokenheartsanddirtywindows.com/about.html |title=Broken Hearts and Dirty Windows: The Songs of John Prine; Oh Boy Records |website=Brokenheartsanddirtywindows.com |accessdate=February 18, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120310090639/http://www.brokenheartsanddirtywindows.com/about.html |archive-date=March 10, 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n[[File:John Prine (29217865466).jpg|alt=Prine onstage with a guitar and a microphone|thumb|Prine onstage, 2016]]\nIn 2016, Prine was named winner of the PEN/Song Lyrics Award, given to two songwriters every other year by the [[PEN International|PEN]] New England chapter. The 2016 award was shared with [[Tom Waits]] and his songwriting collaborator wife [[Kathleen Brennan]]. Judges for the award included [[Peter Wolf]], [[Rosanne Cash]], [[Paul Simon]], [[Elvis Costello]] and others, as well as literary judge [[Salman Rushdie]].<ref name=Pen>{{Cite web|url=https://pen.org/|title=Home|website=Pen.org|date=September 20, 2016|access-date=April 8, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170718155703/https://pen.org/|archive-date=July 18, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2016, Prine released ''[[For Better, or Worse]]'', a follow-up to ''[[In Spite of Ourselves]]'' from 1999. The album featured country music covers featuring some of the most prominent female voices in the genre including [[Alison Krauss]], [[Kacey Musgraves]] and [[Lee Ann Womack]], as well as [[Iris DeMent]], the only guest artist to be featured on both albums.<ref name=\"Folk Radio Davies\">{{cite web |last1=Davies |first1=Mike |title=John Prine: For Better, Or Worse |url=https://www.folkradio.co.uk/2016/09/john-prine-better-worse/ |website=Folk Radio |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |date=September 29, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180510090043/http://www.folkradio.co.uk/2016/09/john-prine-better-worse/ |archive-date=May 10, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, 2017 The American Currents exhibit opened at the Country Music Hall of Fame. The exhibit featured a pair of cowboy boots and jacket that he often wore on stage, his personal guitar and the original handwritten lyric to his hit, \"Angel From Montgomery.\" The American Currents Class of 2016 showcased artists who made a significant impact on country music in 2016, including [[Jason Aldean]], [[Kelsea Ballerini]], [[Ross Copperman]], [[The Earls of Leicester (band)|The Earls of Leicester]], [[Brett Eldredge]], [[Florida Georgia Line]], [[Mickey Guyton]], [[Natalie Hemby]], [[Sierra Hull]], [[Jason Isbell]], [[Miranda Lambert]], [[Jim Lauderdale]], [[Shane McAnally]], [[Lori McKenna]], [[William Michael Morgan]], [[Maren Morris]], [[Jon Pardi]], [[Dolly Parton]], [[Margo Price]], John Prine, [[RaeLynn]], [[Chris Stapleton|Chris and Morgane Stapleton]] and [[Randy Travis]]. Prine won his second Artist of the Year award at the 2017 [[Americana Music Honors & Awards]] after previously winning in 2005.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/john-prine-sturgill-simpson-triumph-at-2017-americana-honors-awards-198811/|title=John Prine, Sturgill Simpson Triumph at 2017 Americana Honors & Awards|last=Moss|first=Marissa R.|date=September 14, 2017|website=Rolling Stone|language=en-US|access-date=April 8, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307184257/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-country/john-prine-sturgill-simpson-triumph-at-2017-americana-honors-awards-198811/|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn February 8, 2018, Prine announced his first new album of original material in 13 years, titled ''[[The Tree of Forgiveness]]'', would be released on April 13. Produced by [[Dave Cobb]], the album was released on Prine's own Oh Boy Records and features guest artists [[Jason Isbell]], [[Amanda Shires]], [[Dan Auerbach]] and [[Brandi Carlile]]. Alongside the announcement, Prine released the track \"Summer's End\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/allsongs/2018/02/08/584219320/john-prine-to-release-his-first-album-of-new-songs-in-13-years |title=John Prine To Release His First Album Of New Songs In 13 Years |date=February 8, 2018 |work=NPR |first=Jacob |last=Ganz |access-date=February 9, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180208204744/https://www.npr.org/sections/allsongs/2018/02/08/584219320/john-prine-to-release-his-first-album-of-new-songs-in-13-years |archive-date=February 8, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> The album became Prine's highest-charting album on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8366469/jason-aldean-scores-rearview-town-no-1-billboard-200|title= Jason Aldean Scores Fourth No. 1 on Billboard 200 Albums Chart With 'Rearview Town'|date= April 22, 2018|first= Keith|last= Caulfield|work= Billboard|access-date= April 23, 2018|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180422221345/https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8366469/jason-aldean-scores-rearview-town-no-1-billboard-200|archive-date= April 22, 2018|url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nPrine was married three times. His first marriage was to high school sweetheart Ann Carole in 1966. The marriage lasted until the late 1970s. Prine was married to bassist Rachel Peer from 1984-88. Prine married Fiona Whelan Prine, who was also his manager, in 1996.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/e96aea5d3a1d9dd2c27ebeb88a61df28|title=John Prine in critical condition with COVID-19 symptoms|date=March 29, 2020|website=AP NEWS|access-date=March 30, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330004919/https://apnews.com/e96aea5d3a1d9dd2c27ebeb88a61df28|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Prine and Whelan had three sons together, Tommy, Jack, and Jody. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2020-04-08/john-prine-wife-fiona-whelan-prine-reaction|title=John Prine's Widow Mourns his Death from COVID-19|last=D'Zurilla|first=Christie|date=April 8, 2020|website=Los Angeles Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 10, 2020}}</ref>. Prine had a home, and spent part of the year, in Galway, Ireland.\n\n=== Health problems ===\nIn early 1998, Prine was diagnosed with [[Squamous cell carcinoma|squamous cell cancer]] on the right side of his neck. He had major surgery to remove a substantial amount of diseased tissue, followed by six weeks of [[radiation therapy]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jpshrine.org/john_prine_letter.html |title=John Prine personal letter to his fans about his cancer |website=Jpshrine.org |accessdate=March 15, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101125221035/http://jpshrine.org/john_prine_letter.html |archive-date=November 25, 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref> The surgery removed a piece of his neck and severed a few nerves in his tongue, while the radiation damaged some salivary glands. A year of recuperation and speech therapy was necessary before he could perform again.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/10/arts/music/john-prine-endures-with-a-half-smile-and-a-song.html | title=John Prine Endures, With a Half-Smile and a Song | newspaper=[[The New York Times]] | date=April 6, 2016 | access-date=May 10, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180511015019/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/10/arts/music/john-prine-endures-with-a-half-smile-and-a-song.html | archive-date=May 11, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref> The operation altered his vocals, and added a gravelly tone to his voice.<ref>[http://home.mchsi.com/~rburhead/2005/05concertreviews_IL.htm John Prine concert reviews] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110526024957/http://home.mchsi.com/~rburhead/2005/05concertreviews_IL.htm |date=May 26, 2011 }} June 4, 2005</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Prine underwent surgery to remove cancer in his left lung. After the surgery, a physical therapist put him through an unusual workout to build stamina: Prine was required to run up and down his house stairs, grab his guitar while still out of breath and sing two songs. Six months later, he was touring again.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n=== Death ===\nOn March 19, 2020, amid [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|the coronavirus pandemic in the United States]], Prine's wife Fiona revealed that she had tested positive for the [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2 virus]] and had been quarantined in their home apart from him.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/music/news/john-prine-in-critical-condition-after-hospitalization-for-coronavirus/ar-BB11SC6n|title=John Prine in Critical Condition After Hospitalization for Coronavirus|work=[[MSN]]|access-date=March 29, 2020|date=March 30, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330132524/https://www.msn.com/en-us/music/news/john-prine-in-critical-condition-after-hospitalization-for-coronavirus/ar-BB11SC6n|archive-date=March 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He was hospitalized on March 26 after experiencing [[COVID-19]] symptoms and was [[Intubation|intubated]] on the evening of March 28 in critical condition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/john-prine-covid-19-symptoms-974909/|title=John Prine Hospitalized with COVID-19 Symptoms: 'His Situation Is Critical'|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=March 29, 2020|date=March 29, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329224329/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/john-prine-covid-19-symptoms-974909/|archive-date=March 29, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On March 30, Fiona tweeted that she had recovered and that John was in stable condition but not improving.<ref>{{cite web |title=Singer John Prine is in stable condition, his wife says |url=https://apnews.com/9590a8f408545383d221b20cde37816c |website=AP NEWS |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |language=en |date=March 30, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200330215452/https://apnews.com/9590a8f408545383d221b20cde37816c |archive-date=March 30, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2020-03-30/john-prine-coronavirus-stable|title=John Prine, still hospitalized with COVID-19, is now stable, his wife says|last=D'Zurilla|first=Christie|date=March 30, 2020|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=April 1, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331200420/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2020-03-30/john-prine-coronavirus-stable|archive-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On April 3, she reported that he was still on a ventilator and needed quite a bit of help with his breathing: he had [[pneumonia]] in both lungs and had developed some peripheral issues that were being treated with medications including antibiotics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/john-prine-covid-19-update-977746/?fbclid=IwAR0o9yz_1MEK55qfwuzJi-xtXGyplm9PLzmuOGlnOsTaUYNjghOkl6lSFkg|title=John Prine's Wife Fiona: 'He Is Very Ill and Yet I Remain Hopeful'|last=Doyle|first=Patrick|date=April 3, 2020|publisher=[[Rolling Stone]]|access-date=April 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408093721/https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/john-prine-covid-19-update-977746/?fbclid=IwAR0o9yz_1MEK55qfwuzJi-xtXGyplm9PLzmuOGlnOsTaUYNjghOkl6lSFkg|archive-date=April 8, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Prine died on April 7, 2020, of complications caused by COVID-19.<ref name=\"nyt-obit-grimes\">{{cite news |last1=Grimes |first1=William |authorlink=William Grimes (journalist) |title=John Prine, Who Chronicled the Human Condition in Song, Dies at 73 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/07/arts/music/john-prine-dead.html |accessdate=April 8, 2020 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408012008/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/07/arts/music/john-prine-dead.html |archive-date=April 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Influence ==\nPrine is widely regarded as one of the most influential songwriters of his generation.<ref name=\"Pond The Wrap\">{{cite news |last1=Pond |first1=Steve |title=John Prine, Revered Singer-Songwriter, Dies at 73 From Coronavirus |url=https://www.thewrap.com/john-prine-dies-73-coronavirus/ |access-date=April 7, 2020 |work=The Wrap |date=April 7, 2020 |quote=John Prine, one of the most influential and revered folk and country songwriters of the last 50 years and an unassuming man who was still producing quality work after two bouts with cancer, has died at the age of 73 after being infected with the COVID-19 virus&nbsp;... through two dozen albums over nearly 40 years, Prine remained a hugely influential songwriter who was held in high esteem by his peers in folk and country music. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408030821/https://www.thewrap.com/john-prine-dies-73-coronavirus/ |archive-date=April 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"NYT Barry\">{{cite news |last1=Barry |first1=Dan |title=John Prine Endures, With a Half-Smile and a Song |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/10/arts/music/john-prine-endures-with-a-half-smile-and-a-song.html |access-date=April 7, 2020 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 6, 2016 |quote=Many tough days have been made better by Mr. Prine, the influential singer and songwriter with a gift for articulating moments almost beyond words. His songs have won the respect of Johnny Cash, Kris Kristofferson, Pink Floyd, the Library of Congress, you name it. One admirer, Bob Dylan, once described his canon as 'pure Proustian existentialism' and 'Midwestern mind trips to the nth degree.' |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408035332/https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/10/arts/music/john-prine-endures-with-a-half-smile-and-a-song.html |archive-date=April 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian Beaumont-Thomas\">{{cite news |last1=Beaumont-Thomas |first1=Ben |title=John Prine, US folk and country songwriter, dies aged 73 due to Covid-19 complications |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/08/john-prine-us-folk-and-country-songwriter-dies-aged-73 |access-date=April 7, 2020 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=April 7, 2020 |quote='We join the world in mourning the passing of revered country and folk singer/songwriter John Prine,' the Recording Academy said in a written statement. 'Widely lauded as one of the most influential songwriters of his generation, John's impact will continue to inspire musicians for years to come. We send our deepest condolences to his loved ones.' |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200408020634/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2020/apr/08/john-prine-us-folk-and-country-songwriter-dies-aged-73 |archive-date=April 8, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>  He was called, \"the [[Mark Twain]] of songwriting\".<ref>{{Cite news |last=Doyle |first=Patrick |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/inside-the-life-of-john-prine-the-mark-twain-of-american-songwriting-115459/ |title=Inside the Life of John Prine, the Mark Twain of American Songwriting |date=2017-01-04 |work=Rolling Stone |access-date=2020-04-09 |language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Leimkuehler |first=Matthew |url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/entertainment/music/2020/04/07/john-prine-obituary-singer-songwriter-covid-19/1807915001/ |title=John Prine, the Mark Twain of modern songwriting, dies at age 73 |work=Nashville Tennessean |access-date=2020-04-09 |language=en-US |via=USA Today}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, [[Bob Dylan]] told ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' that Prine was one of his favorite writers, stating \"Prine's stuff is pure [[Marcel Proust|Proustian]] [[existentialism]]. Midwestern mindtrips to the nth degree. And he writes beautiful songs. I remember when [[Kris Kristofferson]] first brought him on the scene. 'Sam Stone' featuring the wonderfully evocative line: 'There\u2019s a hole in daddy's arm where all the money goes, and Jesus Christ died for nothing I suppose.'<ref>\"Prine, John\", ''Encyclopedia of Popular Music'', 4th ed. Ed. Colin Larkin. Oxford Music Online. Oxford University Press. Web. September 27, 2014</ref> All that stuff about 'Sam Stone', the soldier junkie daddy, and 'Donald and Lydia', where people make love from ten miles away. Nobody but Prine could write like that.\"<ref name=\"huff_post_dylan\">{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/04/15/bob-dylan-exclusive-inter_n_187216.html|title=Bob Dylan Exclusive Interview: Reveals His Favorite Songwriters, Thoughts On His Own Cult Figure Status|last=Flanagan|first=Bill|date=April 15, 2009|work=[[HuffPost|Huffington Post]]|access-date=July 12, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090722235252/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/04/15/bob-dylan-exclusive-inter_n_187216.html|archive-date=July 22, 2009|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Johnny Cash]], in his autobiography ''[[Cash: The Autobiography|Cash]]'', wrote, \"I don't listen to music much at the farm, unless I'm going into songwriting mode and looking for inspiration. Then I'll put on something by the writers I've admired and used for years&nbsp;\u2014 [[Rodney Crowell]], John Prine, [[Guy Clark]], and the late [[Steve Goodman]] are my Big Four&nbsp;...\"<ref name=\"cash_prine\">{{cite book|last1=Cash|first1=Johnny |first2=Patrick |last2=Carr |title=Cash: The Autobiography|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|year=2003|page=189|ISBN=}}</ref>\n\n[[Roger Waters]], when asked by ''[[Word Magazine]]'' in 2008 if he heard [[Pink Floyd]]'s influence in newer British bands like [[Radiohead]], replied, \"I don't really listen to Radiohead. I listened to the albums and they just didn't move me in the way, say, John Prine does. His is just extraordinarily eloquent music&nbsp;\u2014 and he lives on that plane with [[Neil Young]] and Lennon.\"<ref name=\"word_waters\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wordmagazine.co.uk/content/word-exclusive-roger-waters|title=Word Interview Exclusive: Roger Waters|work=Word Magazine|date=April 13, 2008|access-date=July 12, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081024104158/http://www.wordmagazine.co.uk/content/word-exclusive-roger-waters|archivedate=October 24, 2008}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and honors ==\n=== Grammy Awards ===\nThe [[Grammy Awards]] are annually presented by [[The Recording Academy]] for outstanding achievements and artistic excellence in the recording arts. Prine won two Grammy Awards out of eleven nominations as well as a [[Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/john-prine|title=John Prine|publisher=[[The Recording Academy]]|website=grammy.com|access-date=March 30, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190325190653/https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/john-prine|archive-date=March 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|+Grammy Award nominations for John Prine\n|-\n! Year\n! Nominated work\n! Category\n! Result\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1972\n| ''[[John Prine (album)|John Prine]]''\n| [[Grammy Award for Best New Artist|Best New Artist]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1986\n| ''[[German Afternoons]]''\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Folk Album|Best Contemporary Folk Recording]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1988\n| ''[[John Prine Live]]''\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Folk Album|Best Contemporary Folk Recording]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1991\n| ''[[The Missing Years (album)|The Missing Years]]''\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Folk Album|Best Contemporary Folk Album]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1995\n| ''[[Lost Dogs and Mixed Blessings]]''\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Folk Album|Best Contemporary Folk Album]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1997\n| ''[[Live on Tour]]''\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Folk Album|Best Contemporary Folk Album]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 1999\n| ''[[In Spite of Ourselves]]''\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Folk Album|Best Contemporary Folk Album]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| 2005\n| ''[[Fair & Square]]''\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Contemporary Folk Album|Best Contemporary Folk Album]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |2018\n| ''[[The Tree of Forgiveness]]''\n| [[Grammy Award for Best Americana Album|Best Americana Album]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |2018\n| \"Summer's End\" \n| [[Grammy Award for Best American Roots Song|Best Americana Roots Song]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |2018\n| \"Knockin' on Your Screen Door\"\n| [[Grammy Award for Best American Roots Song|Best Americana Roots Song]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" |2020\n| John Prine\n| [[Grammy Lifetime Achievement Award|Lifetime Achievement Award]]\n| {{won}}\n|}\n\n===Other accolades===\n*During 2005 at the request of [[United States Poet Laureate|U.S. Poet Laureate]] [[Ted Kooser]], John Prine became the first singer/songwriter to read and perform at the [[Library of Congress]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/today/cyberlc/feature_wdesc.php?rec=3677|title=A Literary Evening with John Prine and Ted Kooser|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|date=March 9, 2005|access-date=May 22, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180728051442/http://www.loc.gov/today/cyberlc/feature_wdesc.php?rec=3677|archive-date=July 28, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*John Prine received six awards from the [[Americana Music Honors & Awards]]: the Lifetime Achievement Award for Songwriting (2003), Artist of the Year (2005, 2017, 2018), Song of the Year for \"[[Summer's End (song)|Summer's End]]\" (2019) and Album of the Year for ''[[The Tree of Forgiveness]]'' (2019).\n*2016, [[PEN International|PEN]] New England Song Lyrics Award.<ref name=Pen/>\n\n== Discography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\" \n|+John Prine studio albums\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n! colspan=\"6\"| Peak chart positions\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Label\n|- style=\"font-size: smaller\"\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[Billboard 200|US]]<br /><ref name=billboard200>{{cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/John-Prine/chart-history/billboard-200 |title=Billboard 200 |work=Billboard 200 |access-date=May 16, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180526095303/https://www.billboard.com/music/John-Prine/chart-history/billboard-200 |archive-date=May 26, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[Top Country Albums|US Country]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/john-prine/chart-history/CLP|title=John Prine Chart History: Country Albums|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180520040740/https://www.billboard.com/music/john-prine/chart-history/country-albums|archive-date=May 20, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[Independent Albums|US Indie]]<br /><ref name=indie>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/john-prine/chart-history/IND|title=John Prine Chart History: Independent Albums|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131220942/https://www.billboard.com/music/John-Prine/chart-history/IND|archive-date=January 31, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[Top Rock Albums|US<br /> Rock]]<br /><ref name=rock>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/john-prine/chart-history/RCK|title=John Prine Chart History: Rock Albums|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201230505/https://www.billboard.com/music/John-Prine/chart-history/RCK|archive-date=February 1, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[Folk Albums|US<br /> Folk]]<br /><ref name=folk>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/john-prine/chart-history/FLK|title=John Prine Chart History: Americana/Folk Albums|work=Billboard|accessdate=April 24, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131213215/https://www.billboard.com/music/John-Prine/chart-history/FLK|archive-date=January 31, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n! style=\"width:45px;\"| [[Canadian Albums Chart|Can]]<br /><ref name=billboardcan>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/music/john-prine/chart-history/CNA|title=John Prine Chart History: Billboard Canada|work=Billboard|access-date=March 30, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200331033527/https://www.billboard.com/music/john-prine/chart-history/CNA|archive-date=March 31, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n| 1971\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | ''[[John Prine (album)|John Prine]]''\n| 154\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| rowspan=\"4\"| [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n|-\n| 1972\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | ''[[Diamonds in the Rough (album)|Diamonds in the Rough]]''\n| 148\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| 1973\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | ''[[Sweet Revenge (John Prine album)|Sweet Revenge]]''\n| 135\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| 1975\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | ''[[Common Sense (John Prine album)|Common Sense]]''\n| 66\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| 1978\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | ''[[Bruised Orange]]''\n| 116\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| rowspan=\"3\"| [[Asylum Records|Asylum]]\n|-\n| 1979\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | ''[[Pink Cadillac (album)|Pink Cadillac]]''\n| 152\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| 1980\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | ''[[Storm Windows]]''\n| 144\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| 1984\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | ''[[Aimless Love]]''\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| rowspan=\"11\"| [[Oh Boy Records|Oh Boy]]\n|-\n| 1986\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | ''[[German Afternoons]]''\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| 1991\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | ''[[The Missing Years (album)|The Missing Years]]''\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| 1993\n|style=\"text-align:left;\" | ''[[A John Prine Christmas]]''\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| 1995\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | ''[[Lost Dogs and Mixed Blessings]]''\n| 159\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| 1999\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | ''[[In Spite of Ourselves]]''\n| 197\n|