gory:Italy under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Italy international footballers]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 1988 players]]\n[[Category:1990 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriate sportspeople in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in England]]\n[[Category:Italian football managers]]\n[[Category:ACF Fiorentina managers]]\n[[Category:S.S. Lazio managers]]\n[[Category:Inter Milan managers]]\n[[Category:Manchester City F.C. managers]]\n[[Category:Galatasaray S.K. (football) managers]]\n[[Category:FC Zenit Saint Petersburg managers]]\n[[Category:Italy national football team managers]]\n[[Category:Serie A managers]]\n[[Category:Premier League managers]]\n[[Category:S\u00fcper Lig managers]]\n[[Category:Russian Premier League managers]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriate football managers]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriate sportspeople in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Italian expatriate sportspeople in Russia]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in England]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Turkey]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Russia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n | name                 = Roberto Mancini\n | image                = Mancini_2017.jpg\n | image_size           = 200\n | caption              = Mancini in 2017\n | fullname             = Roberto Mancini<ref>{{Hugman|13067|accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref>\n | birth_date           = {{birth date and age|1964|11|27|df=y}}<ref name=BDFutbol>{{cite web |url=http://www.bdfutbol.com/en/l/l94062.html |title=Mancini: Roberto Mancini: Manager |website=BDFutbol |accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref>\n | birth_place          = [[Iesi]], Italy\n | height               = 1.79 m<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/players/mancinidata.html|title=Roberto Mancini - Goals in Serie A|website=www.rsssf.com|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n | position             = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n | currentclub          = [[Italy national football team|Italy]] (manager)\n | years1               = 1981\u20131982\n | clubs1               = [[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]]\n | caps1                = 30\n | goals1               = 9\n | years2               = 1982\u20131997\n | clubs2               = [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]]\n | caps2                = 424\n | goals2               = 132\n | years3               = 1997\u20132001\n | clubs3               = [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]]\n | caps3                = 87\n | goals3               = 15\n | years4               = 2001\n | clubs4               = \u2192 [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] (loan)\n | caps4                = 4\n | goals4               = 0\n | totalcaps            = 545\n | totalgoals           = 156\n | nationalyears1       = 1982\u20131986\n | nationalteam1        = [[Italy national under-21 football team|Italy U21]]\n | nationalcaps1        = 26\n | nationalgoals1       = 9\n | nationalyears2       = 1984\u20131994\n | nationalteam2        = [[Italy national football team|Italy]]\n | nationalcaps2        = 36\n | nationalgoals2       = 4\n | manageryears1        = 2001\u20132002\n | managerclubs1        = [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]]\n | manageryears2        = 2002\u20132004\n | managerclubs2        = [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]]\n | manageryears3        = 2004\u20132008\n | managerclubs3        = [[Inter Milan]]\n | manageryears4        = 2009\u20132013\n | managerclubs4        = [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]]\n | manageryears5        = 2013\u20132014\n | managerclubs5        = [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]]\n | manageryears6        = 2014\u20132016\n | managerclubs6        = [[Inter Milan]]\n | manageryears7        = 2017\u20132018\n | managerclubs7        = [[FC Zenit Saint Petersburg|Zenit Saint Petersburg]]\n | manageryears8        = 2018\u2013\n | managerclubs8        = [[Italy national football team|Italy]]\n | medaltemplates = {{MedalCountry|{{fb|ITA}}}}\n{{MedalSport|Men's [[association football|football]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition |[[FIFA World Cup]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[1990 FIFA World Cup|1990 Italy]]|}}\n}}\n\n'''Roberto Mancini''' ({{IPA-it|ro\u02c8b\u025brto man\u02c8t\u0283i\u02d0ni}}; born 27 November 1964) is an Italian [[Association football|football]] manager and former player who is the  manager of the [[Italy national football team|Italy national team]]. As a player, Mancini operated as a [[Forward (association football)#Second striker|deep-lying forward]], and was best known for his time at [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]], where he played more than 550 matches, and helped the team win the [[Serie A]] league title, four [[Coppa Italia]] titles, and the [[European Cup Winners' Cup]]. He was capped 36 times for [[Italy national football team|Italy]], taking part at [[UEFA Euro 1988]] and the [[1990 FIFA World Cup]], achieving semi-final finishes in both tournaments. In 1997, after 15 years at Sampdoria, Mancini left the club to join [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]], where he won a further ''[[List of Italian football champions|Scudetto]]'', as well as the Cup Winners' Cup, the [[UEFA Super Cup]] and two more Coppa Italia titles.\n\nAs a player, Mancini would often give team talks at [[half-time]]. Towards the end of his playing career he became an assistant to [[Sven-G\u00f6ran Eriksson]] at Lazio.<ref>{{cite web |title=FA Cup special: The Roberto Mancini story |last=Whalley |first=Mike |quote=He was the club captain, he often gave the team talks and he even helped to design the kit. |url=http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/sport/football/manchester_city/s/1420688_fa-cup-special-the-roberto-mancini-story |date=13 May 2011 |accessdate=13 May 2011}}</ref> His first manager role was at a cash-stricken [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]] at only 35 years old. He won a Coppa Italia there, but left with the team facing bankruptcy. Months later he took over as manager at Lazio, where again he inherited financial constraints and was forced to lose a number of key players. With limited resources during his two-season tenure, he guided the club to another Coppa Italia.\n\nIn 2004, Mancini was given the chance to manage a major club with more resources when he was offered the manager's job at Inter. During his first tenure at Inter, the club won three consecutive Serie A titles, an Inter club record, and an [[Football records in Italy#Most consecutive wins|Italian record 17 consecutive league game victories]] stretching nearly half a season; Mancini became Inter's most successful manager in 30 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2007/03/01/1860120.htm |title=Inter's winning run ends in draw with Udinese |publisher=Abc.net.au |date=1 March 2007 |accessdate=27 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title=Football managers who never get the job \u2013 Mancini was Inter Milan's most successful manager in 30 years | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/shortlisted-football-managers-who-never-get-the-job-1821650.html?action=Popup&ino=8 | publisher=Independent Online | location=London | first=Simon | last=Rice | date=16 November 2009}}</ref> Despite his domestic success, many pundits saw the repeated failure to win the coveted [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] as the main reason for his dismissal in 2008.\n\nAfter being out of football for over a year, Mancini was appointed [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] manager in December 2009.<ref name=\"tactics\">{{cite news |title=Younger the better for Manchester City manager Roberto Mancini |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/english-football/younger-the-better-for-manchester-city-manager-roberto-mancini-1.1045178 |publisher=heraldscotland.com |date=1 August 2010 |accessdate=1 August 2010}}</ref> Under his stewardship, he instilled a winning culture at the club, taking Manchester City from a mid-table club to the top level of English football, combining defensive solidity with attacking flair. In the [[2010\u201311 in English football|2010\u201311 season]], his first full season at Manchester City, Mancini guided the club to Champions League football and the [[2011 FA Cup Final|FA Cup]], the club's first major trophy in 35 years.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hart on brink of Blues record |last=Ferguson |first=Peter |url=http://www.mcfc.co.uk/News/Team-news/2011/April/Hart-on-brink-of-Blues-record |publisher=Manchester City FC |date=29 April 2011 |accessdate=13 May 2011}}</ref> In the [[2011\u201312 in English football|2011\u201312 season]], Mancini guided Manchester City to the club's first league title in 44 years in an enthralling last day of the season, winning 3\u20132, with two goals in [[Last-minute goal|injury time]] in what was called \"the best match of the best last day of the season in English football history.\"<ref>{{Cite news |title=Mancini Hails 'Incredible' win |last=O'Rourke |first=Pete |publisher=Sky Sports |url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/11679/7754379/Mancini-hails-incredible-win |date=14 May 2012 |accessdate=14 May 2012 |location=Manchester}}</ref> Under Mancini, City progressed to the [[2013 FA Cup Final]], but were defeated by the soon-to-be relegated [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] 1\u20130.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Wigan stun Man City in FA Cup |last=McNulty| first=Phil |publisher=BBC Sport|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22409634 |date=11 May 2013 |accessdate=11 May 2013 |location=London}}</ref> Mancini was sacked two days later,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/22507128|title=Roberto Mancini: Manchester City sack manager|publisher=BBC|date=13 May 2013 }}</ref> before took over at Turkish club [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]] in September 2013, winning the [[Turkish Cup]] in his only season at the club.\n\nRegarded as a cup specialist,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itv.com/sport/football/facup/news/fourth-round-replay-live-itv-man-city-notts-county-tactics-89922/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110325185001/http://www.itv.com/sport/football/facup/news/fourth-round-replay-live-itv-man-city-notts-county-tactics-89922/ |archivedate=25 March 2011 |title=Talking Tactics: Mancini the cup specialist |last=Cox |first=Michael |publisher= ITV |accessdate=28 October 2013}}</ref> Mancini has reached at least a semi-final of a major national cup competition in every season he has been a manager, from 2002 to 2013. He holds a number of records, including most consecutive [[Coppa Italia#Finals|Coppa Italia finals]] from 2004 to 2008, with [[2003\u201304 Coppa Italia|Lazio once in 2004]] and with Inter in the following four seasons.\n\n==Early life==\nMancini was born in the small town of [[Iesi]], Marche on 27 November 1964,<ref name=\"FACTBOX-Roberto Mancini factbox\">{{cite news|title=FACTBOX-Roberto Mancini factbox|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=soccer&id=3417413|accessdate=28 October 2013|agency=Reuter|publisher=ESPN|date=29 May 2008}}</ref> but then moved onto the mountain town of [[Roccadaspide]] and was raised by Aldo and Marianna Mancini along with his younger sister Stephanie. He had served as an [[altar boy]] in his youth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/mancinis-father-flies-in-to-witness-the-city-revolution-28657478.html|title=Mancini's father flies in to witness the City revolution|publisher=belfasttelegraph.co.uk|date=14 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Club career==\n===Sampdoria===\nMancini debuted in [[Serie A]] for [[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]] in 1981.<ref name=\"FACTBOX-Roberto Mancini factbox\"/> The following year, he was bought by [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]], for \u00a32.2 million, whom he played for until 1997.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/soccer/champions-league/mancini-to-return-with-great-style-2941100.html|title=Mancini to return with great style - Independent.ie|publisher=}}</ref> With Sampdoria, he formed a dynamic [[Forward (association football)#Striker|strike]] partnership with [[Gianluca Vialli]], which earned the pair the nickname ''The Goal Twins'' (\"I Gemelli del Gol\", in Italian).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.corrieredellosport.it/news/calcio/serie-a/sampdoria/2016/05/19-11655137/sampdoria_25_anni_dallo_scudetto_di_vialli_e_mancini/|title=Sampdoria: 25 anni dallo scudetto di Vialli e Mancini|publisher=Il Corriere dello Sport|language=Italian|date=19 May 2016|accessdate=18 June 2017}}</ref> Together, they helped the club to its only [[List of Italian football champions|league title]] in [[1990\u201391 Serie A|1991]], four [[Coppa Italia]]s and a [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|Cup Winners' Cup]] in [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup 1989\u201390|1990]]. He also appeared in the [[1992 European Cup Final|final]] of the [[1991\u201392 European Cup]] against [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]. At 27, Mancini sat on the interview panel that selected [[Sven-G\u00f6ran Eriksson]] as manager. Mancini often delivered the team-talk for Sampdoria. He attended board meetings and had a say in transfer business. In [[David Platt (footballer)|David Platt]]'s 1995 autobiography, ''Achieving the Goal'', he described the day he met Sampdoria in Genoa while playing for [[A.S. Bari|Bari]] and, lining up in the tunnel, became aware that Mancini was looking his way. Platt wrote: \"I thought nothing of it until he asked me, very matter-of-factly, if I was staying at Bari. Outright he asked if I wanted to join Sampdoria. Mancini had been at the club years and was almost a son to the president, Paolo Mantovani.\" Mancini kept in touch when Platt moved to [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] and eventually helped bring him to Sampdoria. At that stage, Mancini had established himself as the most powerful voice in the ''Blucerchiati'' dressing room.\n\nAs a teenager at Sampdoria, Mancini was not someone who liked his authority being questioned. After [[Trevor Francis]] signed from [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] in 1982, aggrieved that his place was under threat, the 18-year-old Mancini ended up picking a fight with 28-year-old Francis on the training ground. A similar incident occurred with [[Liam Brady]], who was eight years older. Additionally, [[Juan Sebasti\u00e1n Ver\u00f3n]] tells the story of swearing in Mancini's direction during an argument about a badly-taken corner. After the match, Mancini had stripped off to the waist and was waiting to fight him. \"He is not an easy person, you know,\" Ver\u00f3n says. \"He has this complicated personality.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2012/jan/06/roberto-mancini-sir-alex-ferguson?INTCMP=SRCH | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Daniel | last=Taylor | title=Roberto Mancini is Manchester City's very own Sir Alex Ferguson | date=6 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Lazio===\nWith [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]], Mancini won his second [[List of Italian football champions|''Scudetto'']] and [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|Cup Winners' Cup titles]], as well as two more [[Coppa Italia]]s. In the [[1999\u20132000 Serie A|1999\u201300 season]], Lazio won the ''Scudetto'' and [[1999\u20132000 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]], but Mancini failed to score in 20 matches and later announced his playing retirement. He joined Lazio's coaching staff as Sven-G\u00f6ran Eriksson's number two. In 2011, when asked about Mancini, Eriksson said, \"I took him to Lazio with me and he wanted to be a manager even while he was a player. He was the coach, he was the kit man, he was the bus driver, everything. At Sampdoria he wanted to check that everything was in place before training. Sometimes I would have to tell him: 'Mancio, you have a game to play on Sunday, you will be exhausted if you have to control everything.' But he was like that.\"<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/sven-goran-eriksson-i-liked-city-theyll-win-the-league-ndash-absolutely-2178992.html Sven Goran Eriksson: 'I liked city. they'll win the league \u2013 absolutely' \u2013 News & Comment \u2013 Football]. ''The Independent'' (8 January 2011). Retrieved on 5 May 2012.</ref>\n\n===Leicester City===\nJoining [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] on loan in January 2001,<ref name=\"Mancini's move to Leicester will benefit England\">{{cite news| title = Mancini's move to Leicester will benefit England| url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/leagues/championship/leicestercity/2996761/Mancinis-move-to-Leicester-will-benefit-England.html| publisher = telegraph.co.uk| date = 18 January 2001| accessdate = 2009-10-24 | location=London | first=Henry | last=Winter}}</ref><ref name=\"Mancini's Foxes fate in balance\">{{cite news| title = Mancini's Foxes fate in balance| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/1184723.stm| publisher = BBC Sport| date = 22 February 2001| accessdate = 2013-10-28}}</ref> Mancini made his [[Premier League]] debut against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] at the age of 36, but failed to complete a full 90 minutes in his five appearances for the club.<ref name=\"Just how close were Leicester City to signing Dutch master Johan Cruyff?\">{{cite news| title = Just how close were Leicester City to signing Dutch master Johan Cruyff?| url = http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Just-close-Leicester-City-signing-Dutch-master-Johan-Cruyff/story-12048983-detail/story.html| publisher = www.leicestermercury.co.uk| date = 23 October 2009| accessdate = 2013-10-28| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131029201321/http://www.leicestermercury.co.uk/Just-close-Leicester-City-signing-Dutch-master-Johan-Cruyff/story-12048983-detail/story.html| archivedate = 29 October 2013| df = dmy-all}}</ref> In early February, he was given leave of absence, citing personal reasons. He telephoned the club on 14 February, however, and informed them he would not be returning to England; he had been offered the manager's job at [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]].<ref name=\"Mancini leaves Leicester\">{{cite news| title = Mancini leaves Leicester| url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/leicester-city/2998910/Mancini-leaves-Leicester.html| publisher = telegraph.co.uk| date = 15 February 2001| accessdate = 2013-10-28 | location=London | first=Matt | last=Lawton}}</ref> Despite this, he cites his time at Leicester City as the period during which he fell in love with the English game, and which later prompted him to accept the job at Manchester City.\n\n==International career==\nDespite success at club level, Mancini never became a regular for [[Italy national football team|Italy]]. At the under-21 level, Mancini was part of the team which reached the semi-finals in the [[1984 UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship]] and finished runners-up in [[UEFA U-21 Championship 1986|1986]].<ref name=storiedicalcio.altervista.org>{{cite web|url=http://www.storiedicalcio.altervista.org/roberto_mancini.html|title=Roberto Mancini|publisher=Storie di Calcio|language=Italian|accessdate=23 January 2015}}</ref> He made his [[Italy national under-21 football team|international senior squad]] debut at the age of 19, under [[Enzo Bearzot]], on 26 May 1984, in a 2\u20130 away win against [[Canada national men's soccer team|Canada]] in [[Toronto]];<ref name=\"FACTBOX-Roberto Mancini factbox\"/> he later won 36 caps, and scored four goals for his country.<ref name=figc.it>{{cite web|url=http://www.figc.it/nazionali/DettaglioConvocato|title=Mancini, Roberto|publisher=FIGC|language=Italian|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref> Mancini was a starting player at [[UEFA Euro 1988|Euro 1988]], where Italy reached the semi-finals;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.datasport.it/calcio/2011-2012/nazionali/italia/europei-italia-1988-urss-germania-ovest.htm|title=Europei 1988: il cammino dell'Italia|publisher=Datasport|language=Italian|date=4 June 2012|accessdate=12 November 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141224012957/http://www.datasport.it/calcio/2011-2012/nazionali/italia/europei-italia-1988-urss-germania-ovest.htm|archivedate=24 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> during the tournament, he scored a goal in a 1\u20131 draw against hosts [[Germany national football team|West Germany]], in the opening match of the tournament on 10 June.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://it.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1988/matches/round=212/match=5/index.html|title=Brehme regala un punto prezioso alla Germania|trans-title=Brehme gives a precious point to Germany|publisher=UEFA.com|language=Italian|date=3 January 2012|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref> Mancini was also a non-playing member of [[Azeglio Vicini]]'s Italian squad that finished in third place at the [[1990 FIFA World Cup|1990 World Cup]] on home soil. He was kept out of the side by competition from [[Gianluca Vialli]], [[Salvatore Schillaci]], [[Andrea Carnevale]] and [[Roberto Baggio]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.storiedicalcio.altervista.org/mondiali_1990_mancini.html|title=1990 - ROBERTO MANCINI|publisher=Storie di Calcio|language=Italian|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nMancini's international career ended after a dispute with national team coach [[Arrigo Sacchi]], when Mancini was upset because he would not be guaranteed a first team place at the [[1994 FIFA World Cup|1994 World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1994/maggio/13/sorpresa_Sacchi_rinforza_difesa_co_0_9405135007.shtml|title=sorpresa: Sacchi rinforza la difesa|trans-title=surprise: Sacchi strengthens the defence|publisher=Il Corriere della Sera|language=Italian|author1=Giancarlo Padovan|date=13 May 1994|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref> Fierce competition with other creative forwards for places in the starting line-up, such as [[Gianfranco Zola]], [[Giuseppe Signori]], Roberto Baggio and later [[Francesco Totti]] and [[Alessandro Del Piero]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/1997/11/17/addio-baggio-mancini-italia-senza.html|title=ADDIO BAGGIO E MANCINI E' L' ITALIA SENZA FANTASIA|trans-title=Farewell, Baggio and Mancini It's the Italy without Creativity|publisher=La Repubblica|author1=Corrado Sannucci|language=Italian|date=17 November 1997|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.raisport.rai.it/news/eventi/francia98/199804/25/3541ca060729f/|title=Baggio al mondiale!!!|trans-title=Baggio at the World Cup!!!|publisher=Rai Sport|language=Italian|author1=Dario Di Gennaro|date=25 April 1998|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref> hindered his international opportunities, hastening his self-imposed exile from the Italian national team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.storiedicalcio.altervista.org/zola_espulsione_usa_1994.html|title=Gianfranco Zola a USA 94|trans-title=Gianfranco Zola at USA 94|publisher=Storie di Calcio|language=Italian|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2013/jan/03/zola-mancini-watford-manchester-city|title=Zola and Mancini met on even terms as players but they do not as managers|publisher=The Guardian|author1=Rob Smyth|date=3 January 2013|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/fa-league-cups/i-wanted-to-kick-him-a-few-times-zola-relishing-mancini-showdown-8437813.html|title='I wanted to kick him a few times' \u2013 Zola relishing Mancini showdown|publisher=The Independent|author1=Jack Pitt-Brooke|date=4 January 2013|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nMancini was a creative and technically gifted forward, who was frequently deployed as a [[Forward (association football)#Second striker|supporting striker]] alongside a centre forward, or, on occasion, as an [[Playmaker#Advanced playmakers|offensive playmaker]] in the [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfield]] position later on in his career. A classic [[Squad number (association football)|number 10]] with creativity and vision, as well as accurate passing and finishing ability, he was capable of assisting many goals as well as scoring them himself, due to his eye for the final pass; he was also known for his excellent technique in the air, which enabled him to execute spectacular volleys. An elegant and skilful player, Mancini was also renowned for his flair, ball control and [[Dribbling#Association football|dribbling]] ability, as well as his tactical intelligence. He frequently stood out because of this attribute, as well as due to his leadership. He was often a vocal presence on the football pitch, regularly organising and motivating his teammates, as well as discussing with opponents and arguing with referees.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://forzaitalianfootball.com/2013/06/legends-of-calcio-roberto-mancini/|title=Legend of Calcio: Roberto Mancini|accessdate=12 November 2014}}</ref> He was also highly regarded for his defensive work-rate off the ball.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/1992/08/30/buso-jugovic-la-samp-si-sveglia.html |title=BUSO E JUGOVIC LA SAMP SI SVEGLIA |work=La Repubblica |language=Italian |last1=Massinissa |first1=Gianni |date=30 August 1992 |accessdate=26 October 2019 }}</ref> Mancini is regarded as one of the best Italian players of his generation, and as one of Italy's greatest ever number 10s.<ref name=storiedicalcio.altervista.org/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Squadre/Roma/17-02-2013/rivera-totti-piu-un-numero-10-baggio-piero-mancini-scelgo-lui-9256802452.shtml|title=Rivera vota Totti: \"Meglio di Baggio e Del Piero. E' il pi\u00f9 grande degli ultimi 30 anni\"|publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=18 February 2013|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial career==\n\n===Early years===\nAlthough Mancini had written a research pamphlet entitled ''\"Il Trequartista\"'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/football_focus/8476119.stm |title=England learn from Italy's national training centre |last=Roan|first=Dan|date=18 May 2010|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=23 January 2010}}</ref> which examined the role of an [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfielder]], he had not as yet attained the necessary coaching badges to become a manager. He therefore needed special dispensation from the Italian football authorities to take the post at [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]],<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lawton|first1=Matt|title=Mancini leaves Leicester|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/leicester-city/2998910/Mancini-leaves-Leicester.html|accessdate=5 May 2012|publisher=The Telegraph|date=15 February 2001|location=London}}</ref> which was given on 4 March 2001.<ref name=\"Roberto Mancini: Factfile\">{{cite news|title=Roberto Mancini: Factfile|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/roberto-mancini-factfile-937544|accessdate=16 October 2014|publisher=Manchester Evening News|date=19 December 2009}}</ref> He was out on loan to Leicester City and returned after four matches to take the Fiorentina job<ref name=\"FACTBOX-Roberto Mancini factbox\"/> on 26 February 2001.<ref name=\"ACF Fiorentina \u00bb Manager history\">{{cite web|title=ACF Fiorentina \u00bb Manager history|url=http://www.worldfootball.net/teams/acf-fiorentina/9/|publisher=Worldfootball.net|accessdate=16 October 2014}}</ref> Fiorentina was plagued by financial problems and Mancini made occasional playing appearances himself. According to various sources,<ref name=\"manchestereveningnews.co.uk\">{{cite web |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/manchester_city/s/1187720_hot_100_on_mancini |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121001094316/http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/sport/football/manchester_city/s/1187720_hot_100_on_mancini |archivedate=1 October 2012 |title=Hot 100 on Mancini |publisher= Manchester Evening News|date=30 December 2009 |accessdate=28 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://mancityfans.net/mcfnet/viewtopic.php?f=119&t=29085&sid=93c327229f60a1f36fcfa0121c58e854 |title=Reprint of ''Manchester Evening News'' article on messageboard |publisher=mancityfans.net |accessdate=28 October 2013}}</ref> Mancini sometimes worked unpaid and even received death threats after key players such as [[Rui Costa]] and [[Francesco Toldo]] had to be sold. Despite this, Mancini managed to win the [[Coppa Italia]] before quitting on 11 January 2002,<ref name=\"Roberto Mancini: Factfile\"/> after just ten months in the job, with Fiorentina in the relegation zone of Serie A.<ref name=\"manchestereveningnews.co.uk\"/> Fiorentina were ultimately relegated in June 2002.<ref>{{cite web |title=Fiorentina back where they belong |url=https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=625852.html |publisher=FIFA.com |date=31 October 2007 |accessdate=2010-04-27}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 May 2002, Mancini was appointed manager of Lazio.<ref name=\"Roberto Mancini: Factfile\"/> He was again restricted by financial considerations, having to sell key players such as [[Hern\u00e1n Crespo]] and [[Alessandro Nesta]], and players were forced to take an 80 percent pay cut. In his first season with Lazio, however, the club reached the [[2002\u201303 UEFA Cup#Semi-finals|semi-finals of the UEFA Cup]]. In [[2003\u201304 Serie A|2003\u201304]], Lazio won the [[2003\u201304 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]].<ref>{{cite news | title=Temper and talent help Roberto Mancini stand out from the rest | url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/premier_league/manchester_city/article6963377.ece | publisher=Times Online | date=21 December 2009 | location=London | first=Gabriele | last=Marcotti}}</ref> Lazio finished fourth in 2003 and sixth in 2004. Before the start of the [[2004\u201305 Serie A|2004\u201305 season]], rumours circulated in the Italian press that [[Inter Milan]] had approached Mancini to fill the recently vacated managerial position at the club. Then, in July 2004, Lazio released Mancini from his contract<ref name=\"FACTBOX-Roberto Mancini factbox\"/> and he joined Inter.<ref name=\"Roberto Mancini: Factfile\"/>\n\n===Inter Milan===\n[[File:Roberto Mancini.jpg|thumb|right|Mancini pictured in 2004 as Inter manager.]]\nMancini took over on 7 July 2004.<ref name=\"Roberto Mancini: Factfile\"/> Under Mancini, Inter soon won the club's first domestic trophy since 1989. Inter became the dominant team in Italy. In Mancini's first season, Inter won the [[2004\u201305 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]] with a 3\u20130 victory over [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] at the [[San Siro]]. Inter finished third in [[2003\u201304 Serie A]] and reached the [[2004\u201305 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] [[2004\u201305 UEFA Champions League#Quarter-finals|quarter-finals]] only to be knocked out by city rivals [[A.C. Milan]] 3\u20130 on aggregate.\n\nIn August 2005, Inter won the [[2005 Supercoppa Italiana]] for the second time in their history with a 1\u20130 victory over [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]. Inter again won the [[2005\u201306 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]] and [[2006 Supercoppa Italiana|Italian Super Cup]]. Following the ''[[Calciopoli]]'' scandal, [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] were stripped of the ''[[List of Italian football champions|Scudetto]]'' title, which was handed to Inter instead. Inter achieved a record-breaking run of 17 consecutive victories in [[2006\u201307 Serie A|Serie A]], starting on 25 September 2006, with a 4\u20131 home win over [[A.S. Livorno Calcio|Livorno]] and ending on 28 February 2007 after a 1\u20131 draw at home to [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]]. The run lasted for almost five months and is among the best in [[UEFA|European league football history]]. Inter won a [[2006\u201307 Serie A|second successive league title]] with five games to spare and only losing one league game all season. Inter finished with a record-breaking 97 points.\n\nMancini became the third coach in [[History of Inter Milan|Inter history]] to win back-to-back league titles after [[Alfredo Foni]]; [[1952\u201353 Serie A|1952\u201353]] and [[1953\u201354 Serie A|1953\u201354]] and [[Helenio Herrera]]; [[1964\u201365 Serie A|1964\u201365]] and [[1965\u201366 Serie A|1965\u201366]]). Inter also progressed to the [[2006\u201307 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]] and [[2007 Supercoppa Italiana|Italian Super Cup]] for the third consecutive season, but were beaten in both finals by [[A.S. Roma|Roma]]. Once again, however, Inter struggled in [[UEFA|Europe]]. In the [[2006\u201307 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]], they were knocked out in the [[2006\u201307 UEFA Champions League#First knockout round|first knockout round]] by [[Valencia CF|Valencia]]. At the end of the game, there was a mass brawl involving both sets of players.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/6426453.stm |title=Champions League brawl photos |publisher=BBC News |date=7 March 2007 |accessdate=2010-04-27}}</ref> Mancini was not involved in the incident, but camera footage showed him attempting to block a camera's view before he was seen shrugging his shoulders and walking away. This was Mancini's fourth, and final, season in charge of Inter. His reputation continued to grow as he added a third consecutive [[2007\u201308 Serie A|Serie A title]] to his honours. Again he guided Inter to the [[2007\u201308 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia final]], but lost for a second consecutive season to Roma, 2\u20131, at the [[Stadio Olimpico]].\n\nDespite his successes, the inability to make any real progress in the Champions League displeased Inter owner [[Massimo Moratti]]. Inter were knocked out in the [[2007\u201308 UEFA Champions League#First knockout round|first knockout round]] of the [[2007\u201308 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] by [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]].<ref name=\"FACTBOX-Roberto Mancini factbox\"/> The first leg took place at [[Anfield]], with defender [[Marco Materazzi]] being sent off in the 30th minute. Inter almost held out for a draw, but two late goals in the 85th and 90th minute by Liverpool damaged Inter's hopes of progressing.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Liverpool 2\u20130 Inter Milan |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/7250324.stm |work=BBC Sport |date=19 February 2008 |accessdate=28 October 2012 |first=Sam |last=Lyon}}</ref> The return leg was at the [[San Siro]], but again Mancini was not helped by the ill discipline of his players, with [[Nicol\u00e1s Burdisso]] being sent off in the 50th minute before [[Fernando Torres]] scored for Liverpool in the 64th minute to seal the tie 3\u20130 on aggregate.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Inter Milan 0\u20131 Liverpool (0\u20133) |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/7285152.stm |work=BBC Sport |date=11 March 2008 |accessdate=28 October 2013 |first=Phil |last=McNulty}}</ref> After being eliminated by Liverpool, Mancini wanted to leave after the season, but changed his mind the following day.<ref name=\"FACTBOX-Roberto Mancini factbox\"/>\n\nIn March 2008, amid rumours that he was to be sacked and replaced by [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] manager [[Jos\u00e9 Mourinho]] at the end of the season, Mancini announced his intention to step down at the end of the [[Serie A 2007\u201308|2007\u201308 season]]. He rescinded this decision a day later after meeting with Moratti.<ref name=\"fortune\">{{cite news |title=Roberto Mancini arrives at Manchester City, kissed by fortune |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/dec/19/roberto-mancini-manchester-city |publisher=Guardian.co.uk |date=19 December 2009 |accessdate=2010-12-19 | location=London | first=Kevin | last=Buckley}}</ref> On 29 May 2008, however, Inter officially announced the sacking of Mancini.<ref name=\"Inter Milan dismiss coach Mancini\">{{cite news|title=Inter Milan dismiss coach Mancini|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/7426549.stm|accessdate=17 October 2014|date=29 May 2008|work=BBC News}}</ref> Moratti justified the sacking by pointing to Mancini's comments after the Liverpool defeat.<ref name=\"mancini_inter\">{{cite news |url=http://www.inter.it/aas/news/reader?N=29393&L=en|publisher=FC Internazionale Milano |accessdate=29 May 2008 |date=29 May 2008 |title=F.C. Internazionale statement}}</ref> He was replaced by Mourinho.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mourinho set to replace ousted Mancini |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/may/28/2 |publisher=Guardian.co.uk |date=28 May 2008 |accessdate=3 February 2010 | location=London | first=Dominic | last=Fifield}}</ref>\n\n===Out of football===\nMancini was linked to the vacant Chelsea manager's position in May 2008<ref>{{cite news |title=Hughes & Mancini on Chelsea list |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/7419889.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=28 May 2008 |accessdate=2013-10-28}}</ref> and then the same role at [[Notts County F.C.|Notts County]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Mancini Notts County link denied |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/8304946.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=13 October 2009 |accessdate=2013-10-28}}</ref> On 30 October 2009, Mancini won compensation for his sacking by Inter.<ref>{{cite news  |url=http://www.inter.it/aas/news/reader?N=32524&L=en |publisher=FC Internazionale Milano |accessdate=2009-10-31 |date=31 October 2009 |title=Statement: Roberto Mancini contract terminated}}</ref> The contract settlement, however, meant Mancini was actually unemployable by any other club from May 2008 to October 2009. It was rumoured that Mancini was entitled to a \u20ac16 million pay-off, but in the end, he reportedly settled for \u20ac5 million.<ref name=\"fortune\"/>\n\n===Manchester City===\n\n====2009\u201310====\nOn 19 December 2009, Mancini was publicly revealed to be taking over as manager of [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] on a three-and-a-half-year deal following the sacking of [[Mark Hughes]].<ref name=\"Roberto Mancini: Factfile\"/> With wealthy Emirati owners who were willing to invest heavily in the team, Manchester City had become a club expectant of success.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/mancini-linked-to-city-after-dinnertable-negotiations-1297827.html|title= Mancini linked to City after dinner-table negotiations|last=Burt|first=Jason|date=10 January 2009|work=The Independent|accessdate=1 January 2010 | location=London}}</ref> Having been appointed halfway through the season, Mancini's arrival had an immediate impact on City's form, with four consecutive wins.\n\nMancini won his first [[Manchester Derby]] over [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] 2\u20131 in a [[2009\u201310 Football League Cup|League Cup]] [[2009\u201310 Football League Cup#Semi-finals|semi-final]] [[2009\u201310 Football League Cup#First leg|first leg]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Man City 2\u20131 Man Utd |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_cup/8465407.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=19 January 2010 |accessdate=2010-01-20 | first=Phil | last=McNulty}}</ref> United won the [[2009\u201310 Football League Cup#Second leg|second-leg]] 3\u20131, however, and eliminated City from the competition. In April, City moved into fourth place in the [[2009\u201310 Premier League|Premier League]]. On 5 May, however, a single goal defeat at home to [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] meant that City missed out on a [[2010\u201311 UEFA Champions League|Champions League spot]]. City finished [[2009\u201310 Premier League|the season]] in fifth place, their highest [[Premier League]] finish.<ref>{{cite news | title=West Ham 1\u20131 Man City | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/8666056.stm | publisher=BBC Sport | date=9 May 2010 | first=Phil | last=Dawkes}}</ref> There had been speculation that Mancini might lose his job if City failed to secure Champions League football, but chairman [[Khaldoon Al Mubarak]] gave his support to Mancini.<ref name=\"chairman\">{{cite news | title=Chairman exclusive | url=http://www.mcfc.co.uk/Video/Interviews/Chairman-exclusive | publisher=mcfc.co.uk | date=7 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n====2010\u201311====\n[[File:Roberto Mancini - Lech - Manchester 005.jpg|thumb|right|Mancini as Manchester City manager in 2010.]]\nMancini spent heavily during summer transfer window. He signed German international defender [[J\u00e9r\u00f4me Boateng]] from [[Hamburger SV]] for approximately \u00a310.64 million,<ref>{{cite news | title=Manchester City sign Hamburg's Jerome Boateng | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/8672609.stm | publisher=BBC Sport | date=5 June 2010}}</ref> [[2010 FIFA World Cup Final|Spanish World Cup winner]] [[David Silva]] from [[Valencia CF|Valencia]] for approximately \u00a324 million,<ref>{{cite news | title=Manchester City complete \u00a354m David Silva transfer | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/8775740.stm | publisher=BBC Sport | date=14 July 2010}}</ref> [[Yaya Tour\u00e9]] from [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] for around \u00a324 million<ref>{{cite news | title=Manchester City sign midfielder Yaya Toure | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/8783455.stm | publisher=BBC Sport | date=2 July 2010}}</ref> and [[Aleksandar Kolarov]] from Lazio for approximately \u00a316 million.<ref>{{cite news | title=City sign Kolarov | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/8829949.stm | publisher=BBC Sport | date=24 July 2010 | first=Chris | last=Bevan}}</ref>\nThe [[2010\u201311 Premier League]] season was marked by runs of mixed form. With a 2\u20130 win away at [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] on 19 September 2010, City moved into fourth position in the league and did not drop out of the top four positions during the rest of the season. In October and November, the team struggled for form, which put some pressure on Mancini,<ref>{{Cite news |title=Roberto Mancini claims he is under fire at Manchester City because he is Italian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/nov/05/roberto-mancini-manchester-city-italian |work=Guardian Media Group |date=5 November 2011 |accessdate=23 May 2011 |location=London}}</ref> with his tactics widely criticised following two consecutive 0\u20130 home draws with Manchester United and [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Cautious City pass up golden chance to land blow on United|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/cautious-city-pass-up-golden-chance-to-land-blow-on-united-2130857.html|publisher=The Independent |date=11 November 2010 |accessdate=29 January 2011 |location=London |first=Sam |last=Wallace}}</ref>\n\nA fine run of form in the weeks running up to Christmas, however, meant City occupied first place in the Premier League twice over the Christmas period. In the ten games before 15 January 2011, City won seven times, drew twice and lost only once as they moved into title contention, while also securing passage into the [[2010\u201311 UEFA Europa League#Round of 32|Round of 32 of the]] [[2010\u201311 UEFA Europa League|Europa League]] by finishing as the top team in [[2010\u201311 UEFA Europa League#Group A|Group A]]. As a result of his team's strong league form, Mancini was awarded the [[Premier League Manager of the Month]] award for December.<ref name=\"FA Premier League\">{{cite web|url=http://www.premierleague.com/page/Headlines/0,,12306~2261295,00.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111106135232/http://www.premierleague.com/page/Headlines/0%2C%2C12306~2261295%2C00.html |archivedate= 6 November 2011 |title=Mancini and Nasri receive Barclays awards |publisher=(FA Premier League) |date=7 January 2011 |accessdate=28 October 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nCity's Premier League form tailed off again in the new year, with City jointly contesting the [[2010\u201311 FA Cup|FA Cup]] and Europa League, and Mancini cited burnout for losing ground in the league title race.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Manchester City boss Roberto Mancini: We were so tired |last=Brennan |first=Stuart |url=http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/sport/football/manchester_city/s/1411392_manchester_city_boss_roberto_mancini_we_were_so_tired |work=MEN Media |date=21 March 2011 |accessdate=23 May 2011}}</ref> City were eventually eliminated from the Europa League by Ukrainian side [[FC Dynamo Kyiv|Dynamo Kyiv]] in March, but his team replied strongly by winning eight out of the next ten matches, including an [[2010\u201311 FA Cup#Semi-finals|FA Cup semi-final]] victory at [[Wembley Stadium|Wembley]] over local rivals Manchester United in April.\n\nA win over Tottenham in May guaranteed City the opportunity to play [[2011\u201312 UEFA Champions League|Champions League football]] the following season. This win was followed by City winning the [[2010\u201311 FA Cup|FA Cup]] with a 1\u20130 victory over [[Stoke City F.C.|Stoke City]] in the following weekend's [[2011 FA Cup Final|final]] at Wembley. This [[FA Cup]] triumph meant that Mancini joined five other [[List of Manchester City F.C. managers|City managers]] who had won major honours, and it ended the club's longest trophy drought in [[History of Manchester City F.C.|its history]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itv.com/sport/football/facup/news/video-mancini-on-facup-final-24596/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110419074300/http://www.itv.com/sport/football/facup/news/video-mancini-on-facup-final-24596/ |archivedate=19 April 2011 |title=Roberto Mancini on Manchester City's FA Cup win over Manchester United |publisher= ITV |accessdate=28 October 2013}}</ref><ref>[http://mcfc.co.uk/News/Match-reports/2011/May/FA-Cup-Final-City-v-Stoke-match-report Match report on Manchester City v Stoke City in the FA Cup final 14 May 2011 \u2013 Manchester City FC]. Mcfc.co.uk (14 May 2011). Retrieved on 2012-05-05.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/fa-cup/8514022/FA-Cup-final-Manchester-City-1-Stoke-City-0-match-report.html|title=Manchester City 1 Stoke City 0 match report|date=16 May 2011|work=Daily Telegraph|accessdate=16 May 2011|location=London|first=Duncan|last=White}}</ref>\nDue to their late run of form, City finished third in the league ahead of [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] after a 2\u20130 win over [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] on the last day of the season, thereby avoiding the need to participate in [[2011\u201312 UEFA Champions League#Play-off round|play-off]] round fixtures in order to progress to the group stages of the following season's [[2011\u201312 UEFA Champions League|Champions League competition]]. Only goal difference separated City from achieving a second-place finish over [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]].\n\n====2011\u201312====\nThe club were quieter in the closed season transfer window than in previous years, with the club's spending of approximately \u00a375 million more in line with the corresponding amounts spent by rivals Manchester United and [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]]. \u00a360 million of this sum was used to purchase two players: [[Sergio Ag\u00fcero]], for a club record fee, and [[Samir Nasri]] from [[Atl\u00e9tico Madrid]] and Arsenal respectively. Other players purchased during the summer included [[Ga\u00ebl Clichy]] and [[Stefan Savi\u0107]], while [[Owen Hargreaves]] joined on a free transfer after having been released by Manchester United. City began the [[2011\u201312 Premier League|Premier League season]] very strongly, winning 12 of their first 14 matches and scoring an impressive 48 goals while only conceding 13. These results left City undefeated and five points clear at the top of the league over second-placed Manchester United by the beginning of December.\n\nA revitalised [[Edin D\u017eeko]] won the [[Premier League Player of the Month]] award for August 2011, and David Silva won the same award for September 2011. Many were impressed with the impact of Ag\u00fcero and Nasri, which had given City an exciting, attacking verve.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Why Aguero's 30-minute cameo may have been the spark that changes Manchester City for ever |last=Holt |first=Oliver |url=http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/opinion/blogs/mirror-football-blog/Oliver-Holt-opinion-Why-Sergio-Aguero-30-minute-cameo-may-have-been-the-spark-that-changes-Manchester-City-for-ever-article786053.html |newspaper=Daily Mirror |date=15 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Aguero's priceless gifts may be the making of City |last=Lawton |first=James |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/james-lawton-agueros-priceless-gifts-may-be-the-making-of-city-2338587.html |newspaper=The Independent |date=17 August 2011 |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Can Sergio Ag\u00fcero's artillery propel Manchester City to the title? |last=Taylor |first=Daniel |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2011/aug/16/sergio-aguero-manchester-city-debut |newspaper=The Guardian |date=16 August 2011 |location=London}}</ref>\nMancini was also responsible for inflicting United's worst loss since 1955 when his City side won 6\u20131 away at [[Old Trafford]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/15325536.stm | work=BBC News | title=Man Utd 1\u20136 Man City | date=23 October 2011}}</ref> He was named Premier League Manager of the Month as a result of City's strong form in the month of October.\n\nCity maintained the lead in the Premier League over the next five months but struggled in the Champions League in a [[2011\u201312 UEFA Champions League group stage#Group A|group]] that involved [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]], [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]] and [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]]. City failed to progress, but finished third in the group with ten points, normally enough to guarantee qualification into the knock-out stages.\n[[File:Mancini Nasri Aguero.JPG|thumb|Mancini (left), [[Samir Nasri]] and [[Sergio Ag\u00fcero]] with the [[Premier League|Premier League trophy]] during Manchester City's victory parade, May 2012.]]\n\nA 3\u20132 loss to Manchester United in the FA Cup [[2011\u201312 FA Cup|third round]] on 8 January 2012 was bittersweet. City had [[Vincent Kompany]] controversially sent-off in the sixth minute and United managed to create a 3\u20130 lead before half-time against a lacklustre and beleaguered City team. However, after numerous tactical changes from Mancini at half-time, City came out fighting with ten men, a renewed version of the team that had played in the first half.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Roberto Mancini showed Sir Alex Ferguson how to play with 10 men |last=Cox |first=Michael |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2012/jan/09/roberto-mancini-alex-ferguson-tactics |newspaper=The Guardian |date=9 January 2012 |accessdate=2012-05-31 |location=London}}</ref> Two goals from Aleksandar Kolarov and Sergio Ag\u00fcero narrowed the deficit to just one goal. City were in the ascendency and continued to push for an equalising despite having only ten men, but failed to do so with the final whistle. Mancini later believed the match was a seminal moment in the development of his team, demonstrating that City were a better team than United. He believed that the match helped to carve out a fighting spirit that his team had previously lacked.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Roberto Mancini says league title is everything for Manchester City |last=Jackson |first=Jamie |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/may/04/roberto-mancini-manchester-city |date=4 May 2012 |accessdate=2012-05-31 |work=The Guardian |location=London}}</ref>\n\nCity also progressed to the [[2011\u201312 Football League Cup#Semi-finals|League Cup semi-final]], maintaining Mancini's record of reaching a major competition semi-final in every season he has managed. City played Liverpool and conceded an away goal in the first leg with a penalty from [[Steven Gerrard]]. City went to Anfield and led twice with goals from [[Nigel de Jong]] and Edin D\u017eeko, but another penalty from [[Steven Gerrard]] and a goal from [[Craig Bellamy]] meant Liverpool won 3\u20132 on aggregate.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Liverpool 2\u20132 Manchester City |last=McNulty |first=Phil |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/16606933 |work=BBC Sport |date=25 January 2012 |accessdate=2012-05-31}}</ref> On 13 May 2012, City clinched the Premier League title in a dramatic 3\u20132 win over [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]] after originally being 2\u20131 down going into injury time. He became the second Italian manager to win a Premier League title after [[Carlo Ancelotti]]'s Chelsea team in [[2009\u201310 Premier League|2009\u201310]].\n\n====2012\u201313====\nMancini stated pre-season that Manchester City's long-term aim was to win the Champions League.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Manchester City's Roberto Mancini wants Champions League glory next |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/may/14/manchester-city-roberto-mancini-champions-league?intcmp=239 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=14 May 2012 |accessdate=2012-05-31 |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Manchester City's next task is to strike Champions League gold |last=Conn |first=David |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2012/may/14/manchester-city-champions-league |date=14 May 2012 |accessdate=2012-05-31 |work=The Guardian |location=London}}</ref> Mancini declared that he envisaged less transfer activity in the summer, and is content with his attacking strikers.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Manchester City don't need another striker, says Roberto Mancini |url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/sport/football/manchester-city-dont-need-another-striker-says-roberto-mancini-7804379.html |newspaper=Evening Standard |date=30 May 2012 |accessdate=2012-05-31}}</ref> On 9 July 2012, City announced that Roberto Mancini had signed a new five-year deal, meaning that he is contracted with the club until summer 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18774631|title=Roberto Mancini|accessdate=2012-07-09}}</ref> City began the new season by participating in, and winning, the [[2012 FA Community Shield]] against [[2012 FA Cup Final|2012 FA Cup winners]] Chelsea on 12 August 2012 at [[Villa Park]]. Manchester City won 3\u20132 on this occasion. On 21 November 2012, a 1\u20131 draw at home to [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] saw Manchester City and Mancini exit the Champions League at the [[2012\u201313 UEFA Champions League group stage#Group D|group stage]] for the second successive season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/20321630|title=Man City 1\u20131 Real Madrid|date=21 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of the calendar year of 2012, Manchester City were second in the Premier League, seven points behind local rivals Manchester United. In contrast to the 2011\u201312 league season, Mancini's team struggled to score sufficient goals and suffered some poor results in the second half of the season, such as a 3\u20131 loss to [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] on 9 February 2013 (which Mancini described as the worst performance during his time in charge at City) and a 2\u20130 loss to [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] on 16 March. City's poor form led to United capturing the Premier League title on 22 April with a 3\u20130 win over [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] with four games to spare. On 11 May, Manchester City lost to Wigan Athletic 1\u20130 in the [[2013 FA Cup Final]], with a late goal from Wigan's [[Ben Watson (footballer, born July 1985)|Ben Watson]].\n\nOn 14 May, Mancini was sacked as manager of Manchester City two days after City's loss to Wigan in the FA Cup Final.<ref name=\"Roberto Mancini: Manchester City sack manager\">{{cite news|title=Roberto Mancini: Manchester City sack manager|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/22507128|accessdate=17 October 2014|publisher=BBC Sports|date=14 May 2013}}</ref> Speculation over Mancini's future had mounted for months beforehand; a question regarding then-[[M\u00e1laga CF|M\u00e1laga]] manager [[Manuel Pellegrini]] possibly taking Mancini's job in February 2013 provoked an expletive response from Mancini during a press conference.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Manuel Pellegrini verbally agrees to become Manchester City manager |url=http://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/379522/Manuel-Pellegrini-verbally-agrees-to-become-Manchester-City-manager |newspaper=Daily Express |date=22 February 2013 |accessdate=2013-05-15}}</ref> Mancini's public criticism of backroom and playing staff, as well as his distant relationships, alienated the players and the club hierarchy during the last eight months of his tenure.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Roberto Mancini tells Manchester City players to take responsibility |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2013/mar/03/roberto-mancini-manchester-city |work=The Guardian |date=3 March 2013 |accessdate=2013-05-15 |location=London |first=Jamie |last=Jackson}}</ref> On sacking Mancini, the club cited the need for a more \"holistic\" approach for the long-term future of the club, namely a manager passionate for developing players at youth level to create a \"one house football club,\" as City look to open their new \u00a3100 million youth academy at the [[Etihad Campus]] in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Roberto Mancini: Man City exit because of poor relationships |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22523981 |work=BBC Sport |date=14 May 2013 |accessdate=2013-05-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Mancini exit to spark Man City overhaul |url=http://www.espn.co.uk/football/sport/story/207121.html |work=ESPN |date=14 May 2013 |accessdate=2013-05-15}}</ref> With Manchester City, Mancini achieved the fourth-best win percentage in Premier League history, behind only [[Jos\u00e9 Mourinho]], [[Alex Ferguson]] and [[Carlo Ancelotti]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/36393607|title=Jose Mourinho: Manchester United manager's record in numbers|date=27 May 2016|work=BBC}}</ref>\n\nA week after his sacking, Mancini took out a full page advert in the ''[[Manchester Evening News]]'' to say farewell and thank the club's fans&nbsp;\u2013 an act that was reciprocated in the ''[[Gazzetta dello Sport]]'' by Manchester City supporters.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Roberto Mancini: Manchester City fans to thank former boss in advert |last=Conway |first=Richard |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22647123 |work=BBC Sport |date=23 May 2013 |accessdate=2013-05-24}}</ref>\n\n===Galatasaray===\n[[File:Roberto Mancini'13-14.JPG|thumb|right|180px|Mancini managing [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]] in 2013]]\nOn 30 September 2013, Mancini signed a three-year contract with Turkish side [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]], taking over from the previous coach [[Fatih Terim]], who had left to take over as coach of the [[Turkey national football team|Turkish national team]].<ref name=\"Roberto Mancini: Galatasaray appoint ex-Man City boss\">{{cite news|title=Roberto Mancini: Galatasaray appoint ex-Man City boss|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/24325655|accessdate=20 July 2014|publisher=BBC Sports|date=30 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://espnfc.com/news/story/_/id/1568644/galatasaray-name-roberto-mancini-manager-three-year-deal?cc=3888|title=Galatasaray appoint Roberto Mancini|date=30 September 2013|accessdate=30 September 2013|publisher=ESPN FC}}</ref> In his first game in charge, on 2 October against [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] in the [[2013\u201314 UEFA Champions League|2013\u201314 Champions League]], Galatasaray drew 2\u20132 with a late equaliser.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.repubblica.it/sport/calcio/champions/2013/10/02/news/juve-galatasaray_2-2_mancini_fa_lo_scherzo_a_conte-67770505/|title=Juventus-Galatasaray 2-2, Mancini fa lo scherzo a Conte|publisher=repubblica.it|date=2 October 2013|language=Italian}}</ref> After a convincing 3\u20131 victory at home against [[F.C. Copenhagen|Copenhagen]] in the same competition, his Galatasaray side this time defeated reigning Italian champions Juventus 1\u20130 on the crucial matchday six to advance to the last 16 of the tournament, a feat he was unable to achieve with Manchester City over two seasons. Galatasaray there met Chelsea and were eliminated despite drawing the home leg 1\u20131.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Magowan|first1=Alistair|title=Chelsea 2-0 Galatasaray|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26618172|accessdate=11 June 2014|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=18 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nUnder Mancini, Galatasaray won their first 12 [[2013\u201314 S\u00fcper Lig]] home matches, including a 6\u20130 victory over [[Bursaspor]], the highest winning margin in the league as of game week 20.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/spor/futbol/25769982.asp|title=Galatasaray Mancini ile evinde bir ba\u015fka|date=11 February 2014|accessdate=11 February 2014|publisher=hurriyet}}</ref> On 7 May, Galatasaray won 1\u20130 against [[Eski\u015fehirspor]] in the [[2013\u201314 Turkish Cup|2014 Turkish Cup Final]] with a late goal from [[Wesley Sneijder]]. On 11 June, Mancini left the club by mutual consent.<ref name=\"Roberto Mancini: Galatasaray manager leaves club\">{{cite news|title=Roberto Mancini: Galatasaray manager leaves club|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/27790944|accessdate=17 October 2014|publisher=BBC Sports|date=11 June 2014}}</ref> It has been reported by the club's chairman and the spokesperson that the club's transfer policy and the overall budget of the upcoming season was the reason behind the dispute. This was also verified by Mancini: \"When I accepted the coaching post, Gala's aims were different.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2014/jun/11/roberto-mancini-galatasaray-parted-company|title=Roberto Mancini parts company with Galatasaray after just one year|date=11 June 2014|accessdate=11 June 2014|publisher=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\n===Return to Inter===\nOn 14 November 2014, Mancini agreed to a surprise return at his previous club Inter, replacing [[Walter Mazzarri]] at the helm of the ''Nerazzurri''.<ref name=\"Inter Milan confirm Roberto Mancini appointment after Walter Mazzarri exit\">{{cite web|title=Inter Milan confirm Roberto Mancini appointment after Walter Mazzarri exit|url=http://www.espnfc.com/internazionale/story/2146593/inter-milan-confirm-roberto-mancini-appointment-after-walter-mazzarri-exit|website=ESPN FC|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=14 November 2014|date=14 November 2014}}</ref> His first game in charge was against rivals [[A.C. Milan]] in the [[Derby della Madonnina]], which finished in a 1\u20131 draw, with the club's goal scored by [[Joel Obi]].<ref>{{cite news |first1=Brian |last1=Homewood |first2=Mark |last2=Meadows |title=Milan derby ends all square on Mancini's Inter return |url=https://au.sports.yahoo.com/football/news/article/-/25592950/milan-derby-ends-all-square-on-mancini-s-inter-return/ |work=Yahoo Sport |agency=Reuters |date=24 November 2014 |accessdate=23 November 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129104203/https://au.sports.yahoo.com/football/news/article/-/25592950/milan-derby-ends-all-square-on-mancini-s-inter-return/ |archivedate=29 November 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> On 27 November 2014, Mancini's 50th birthday, Inter played the first European match of his second spell, a 2&ndash;1 home win over [[FC Dnipro Dnipropetrovsk|Dnipro Dnipropetrovsk]] to confirm that Inter would top the group with a game remaining.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Menicucci|first1=Paolo|title=Inter make Mancini's day against Dnipro|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2015/matches/round=2000587/match=2014537/postmatch/report/index.html|accessdate=28 November 2014|publisher=UEFA|date=27 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 August 2016 Mancini left Inter on a mutual agreement.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inter.it/en/news/54033/f-c-internazionale-statement|title=F.C. Internazionale statement|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===Zenit Saint Petersburg===\nOn 1 June 2017, Mancini was appointed as a manager of [[FC Zenit Saint Petersburg]].<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[FC Zenit Saint Petersburg]]|url=http://fc-zenit.ru/news/2017-06-01-roberto-manchini-naznachen-glavnym-trenerom-zenita.htm|script-title=ru:\u0420\u043e\u0431\u0435\u0440\u0442\u043e \u041c\u0430\u043d\u0447\u0438\u043d\u0438 \u043d\u0430\u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043d \u0433\u043b\u0430\u0432\u043d\u044b\u043c \u0442\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0440\u043e\u043c \u00ab\u0417\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0430\u00bb|date=1 June 2017|language=Russian}}</ref> On 13 May 2018, Mancini terminated his contract by mutual consent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.football-italia.net/121290/official-mancini-leaves-zenit|title=Official: Mancini leaves Zenit|publisher=Football Italia|date=13 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Italy national team===\nOn 14 May 2018, it was announced that Mancini signed as manager of the [[Italy national football team|Italy national team]] after taking over from [[caretaker manager]], [[Luigi Di Biagio]].<ref name=\"Nazionale2018\">[https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/43687934 Roberto Mancini: Italy appoint former Manchester City manager]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.football-italia.net/121375/official-italy-appoint-mancini|title=Official: Italy appoint Mancini|publisher=Football Italia|date=14 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.football-italia.net/116764/official-di-biagio-italy-friendlies|title=OFFICIAL: Di Biagio for Italy friendlies|publisher=Football Italia|date=5 February 2018}}</ref> Mancini was appointed manager six months after Italy failed to qualify for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] under [[Gian Piero Ventura]], after a [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 UEFA Second Round#Matches|play-off]] defeat to [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]] in November 2017\u2014the first time Italy had failed to qualify for the tournament since the [[1958 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.football-italia.net/112772/ignominious-italy-out-world-cup|title=Ignominious Italy out of World Cup|publisher=Football Italia|date=13 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2017/nov/14/this-is-the-apocalypse-italian-press-mourns-football-world-cup-exit |title=\u2018This is the apocalypse\u2019: Italian press mourns nation\u2019s World Cup exit|date=14 November 2017|work=Guardian|accessdate=14 November 2017}}</ref> Mancini signed an incentive-based contract, which would run until 2020, however, would be given an automatic extension if Italy were to [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying Group J|qualify]] for [[UEFA Euro 2020|Euro 2020]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.football-italia.net/121398/mancini-day-what-we-learned|title=Mancini day - what we learned|publisher=Football Italia|date=15 May 2018}}</ref> On 28 May 2018, Italy won their first match under Mancini, a 2\u20131 victory in a friendly over [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.football-italia.net/122048/italy-balotelli-and-mancini-ideal-start|title=Italy: Balotelli and Mancini ideal start|publisher=Football Italia|date=28 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 October 2019, Italy qualified for Euro 2020 with three matches to spare after a 2\u20130 home win over [[Greece national football team|Greece]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.football-italia.net/145184/italy-perfect-azzurri-qualify-euro-2020|title=Italy: Perfect Azzurri qualify for Euro 2020!|publisher=Football Italia|date=12 October 2019}}</ref> After qualification for Euro 2020, the clause in his contract was triggered, extending his contract to 2022.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.football-italia.net/145231/mancini-extends-italy-deal|title=Mancini extends Italy deal|publisher=Football Italia|date=14 October 2019}}</ref> On 15 October, with a 5\u20130 away win over [[Liechtenstein national football team|Liechtenstein]], Italy won its ninth consecutive match under Mancini, equalling the record set by [[Vittorio Pozzo]] between 1938 and 1939.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.football-italia.net/145287/mancini-equals-pozzo-record|title=Mancini equals Pozzo record|publisher=Football Italia|date=15 October 2019}}</ref> On 15 November, with a 3\u20130 away win against [[Bosnia and Herzegovina national football team|Bosnia and Herzegovina]], he broke Pozzo's record, leading Italy to their tenth consecutive victory, and their record sixth consecutive away victory.<ref name=\"Italy: Dominant display in Bosnia\">{{cite web |url=https://www.football-italia.net/146483/italy-dominant-display-bosnia |title=Italy: Dominant display in Bosnia |publisher=Football Italia |date=15 November 2019 |accessdate=15 November 2019 }}</ref> The record was extended to 11 consecutive wins three days later with a 9\u20131 home win over [[Armenia national football team|Armenia]]; the result also saw Italy win all of their Euro 2020 qualifying matches in Group J, and set an unprecedented record of 10 victories in a single calendar year in 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.football-italia.net/146605/more-records-mancios-azzurri|title=More records for Mancio's Azzurri|publisher=Football Italia|date=18 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.football-italia.net/146607/italy-armenia-annihilated-9-1 |title=Italy: Armenia annihilated 9-1! |publisher=Football Italia |date=18 November 2019 |accessdate=19 November 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Management style==\nDespite having been a support striker during his playing career, Mancini places great emphasis on building from the back, stressing the importance of not conceding a goal means the team will always have an opportunity to win, going as far to say, \"I like 1\u20130 wins. When you don't concede a goal and you have players like [[Edin D\u017eeko]], [[Carlos Tevez]] or [[David Silva]], you win 90%. I prefer we are boring for two to three matches and we win 1\u20130. If you watch teams that won titles, they conceded very few goals.\"<ref>{{Cite news |title=Manchester City need to start being boring again, says Roberto Mancini |last=Rich |first=Tim |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/feb/04/roberto-mancini-manchester-city |work=Guardian |date=4 February 2011 |accessdate=13 May 2011 |location=London}}</ref> Despite this, some argue Mancini is more of a \"defence first\" manager rather than a \"win first\" manager,<ref>{{Cite news |title=Roberto Mancini stands up for Manchester City's defensive tactics |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/jan/06/roberto-mancini-defensive-tactics-arsenal |publisher=guardian.co.uk |date=6 January 2011 |accessdate=7 January 2011 |location=London |first=David |last=Hytner}}</ref> a style that has been criticised by some in the [[Media of the United Kingdom|British media]]. Others accepted that his pragmatic and cautious approach was what the team lacked, and that Mancini's style would ensure City could challenge for trophies regularly.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Roberto Mancini's cautious approach at Manchester City is working, no matter what Arsenal's Cesc Fabregas says |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/manchester-city/8244071/Roberto-Mancinis-cautious-approach-at-Manchester-City-is-working-not-matter-what-Arsenals-Cesc-Fabregas-says.html |publisher=www.telegraph.co.uk |date=6 January 2011 |accessdate=6 January 2011 |location=London |first=Jim |last=White}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Roberto Mancini's scrap merchants show mettle to back up title hopes |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2011/jan/06/roberto-mancini-scrap-merchants-title-hopes |publisher=www.guardian.co.uk |date=6 January 2011 |accessdate=7 January 2011 |location=London |first=Paul |last=Hayward}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Roberto Mancini was right to be so negative against Arsenal, so long as the end result is positive for Manchester City |url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/2896/premier-league/2011/01/06/2291998/roberto-mancini-was-right-to-be-so-negative-against-arsenal |publisher=goal.com |date=6 January 2011 |accessdate=7 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Roberto_Mancini_RED_BULL_STADIUM_JERSEY_NY.jpg|thumb|left|Mancini in 2010]]\nAt Manchester City, Mancini had inherited a team from [[Mark Hughes]], which while showing great prolificacy and potential in front of goal, had an insecure defence. Intensively coaching his defence enabled him to get his tenure at City off to a positive start. In Inter's [[2007\u201308 Serie A|2007\u201308]] Serie A-winning season, Inter conceded the fewest goals in the league with 26, 11 fewer than [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] and [[A.S. Roma|Roma]], and at City, his team gradually garnered a reputation as being well organised defensively and tough to break down. In Mancini's first full season in charge at City, they conceded 33 goals in the Premier League, the fewest along with Chelsea and 18 clean sheets, the highest in the [[2010\u201311 Premier League|2010\u201311 Premier League season]].\n\nMancini's training methods have been criticised by some City players<ref>{{cite news |title=Carlos Tevez criticizes Roberto Mancini's training methods |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/apr/13/carlos-tevez-criticises-roberto-mancini |publisher=guardian.co.uk |date=13 April 2010 |accessdate=26 September 2010 | location=London | first=Daniel | last=Taylor}}</ref> and especially by ex-Manchester City fitness coach [[Raymond Verheijen]], who is a personal fitness coach for [[Craig Bellamy]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ex-coach attacks Roberto Mancini's 'crazy' training at Manchester City |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/sep/23/roberto-mancini-training-methods-manchester-city |publisher=guardian.co.uk |date=23 September 2010 |accessdate=26 September 2010 | location=London | first=Daniel | last=Taylor}}</ref> During his time at City, Mancini tried to stamp his authority with rebellious players who were not performing well and has stated, \"If a top player is not happy then it's better to go.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Roberto Mancini tells Carlos Tevez to shape up or ship out of City |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/apr/29/roberto-mancini-carlos-tevez-city-manchester |publisher=guardian.co.uk |date=29 April 2010 |accessdate=26 September 2010 | location=London | first=Daniel | last=Taylor}}</ref>\n\nMancini is known to use the media to alleviate the pressure from his players. Following City's defeat to [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in the [[2011\u201312 Premier League|2011\u201312 season]], a deficit of eight points had been established between rivals [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] with only six matches left to play. After the Arsenal match, he believed the deficit was catchable.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Manchester City's manager Roberto Mancini says title race is not over |last=Jackson |first=Jamie |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/apr/10/manchester-city-roberto-mancini |newspaper=The Guardian |date=10 April 2012 |accessdate=2012-06-03 |location=London}}</ref> City, however, won the next match convincingly against [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]] 4\u20130, but from then on Mancini maintained in post-match interviews that the title race was over.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Mancini reiterates Premier League title race is over despite Manchester City's 6\u20131 win |url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/2896/premier-league/2012/04/14/3036019/mancini-reiterates-premier-league-title-race-is-over-despite |work=goal.com |date=14 April 2012 |accessdate=2012-05-06}}</ref> City won the next three matches, meaning a win against Manchester United would put them top of the league on goal difference. City beat United 1\u20130, with Mancini conceding the title race was back on \u2013 but that United were favourites with two matches to play.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Mancini: United are favourites |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/1059748/manchester-city's-roberto-mancini:-man-united-are-favourites?cc=5739 |work=ESPN |date=1 May 2012 |accessdate=2012-05-06}}</ref>\nMancini's unorthodox approach worked, and City won the league on goal difference with 89 points after six consecutive league wins in the final six matches. Mancini's players believed his approach alleviated pressure and helped City to win the last six league matches, which won the title on goal difference.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Silva: Mancini mind games helped us |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/1060747/david-silva:-roberto-mancini-mind-games-have-helped-man-city?cc=5739 |work=ESPN |date=2 May 2012 |accessdate=2012-05-06}}</ref> Mancini stated afterwards that he always believed personally that City could win the title, but wanted his players to prove they could despite his public statements suggesting otherwise.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Manchester City manager Roberto Mancini admits he always believed he could win title, despite mind games |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/manchester-city/9264702/Manchester-City-manager-Roberto-Mancini-admits-he-always-believed-he-could-win-title-despite-mind-games.html |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=14 May 2012 |accessdate=2012-06-03 |location=London}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\nThere was much controversy surrounding [[Italy national football team|Italy]]'s [[UEFA Euro 2016 qualifying]] match on 28 March 2015 against [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]], as Italy head coach [[Antonio Conte]] called up Brazilian-born [[\u00c9der (Italian footballer)|\u00c9der]] and Argentine-born [[Franco V\u00e1zquez]]. Both players hold an Italian citizenship as they have relatives that are Italian, allowing them to be eligible to play for Italy. Speaking at a Serie A meeting on 23 March 2015, Mancini said, \"The Italian national team should be Italian. An Italian player deserves to play for the national team while someone who wasn't born in Italy, even if they have relatives, I don't think they deserve to.\" Conte's response to the use of foreign-born players was, \"If [[Mauro Camoranesi]] [who was born in Argentina] was allowed to help Italy win the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]], then why can't \u00c9der and Franco V\u00e1zquez lead the Azzurri to glory in [[UEFA Euro 2016|next year's European Championship]]?\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.us/italy/story/2363437/antonio-conte-defends-use-of-foreign-born-players-on-italy-squad|title=Antonio Conte defends use of foreign-born players on Italy squad|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nFollowing a heated exchange between Mancini and [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]] coach [[Maurizio Sarri]] in the final minutes of a [[Coppa Italia]] match on 20 January 2016, Mancini accused Sarri of being a [[homophobe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2016/jan/19/internazionale-napoli-roberto-mancini-maurizio-sarri|title=Inter\u2019s Roberto Mancini: Napoli manager Maurizio Sarri called me a faggot|first=Marcus|last=Christenson|date=19 January 2016|publisher=|via=The Guardian}}</ref> Sarri responded to the accusations by affirming that he wasn't a homophobe, and that \"what happens on the field, stays on the field\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Serie-A/Napoli/19-01-2016/napoli-sarri-ero-nervoso-ma-ho-chiesto-scusa-sono-cose-che-succedono-campo-140328584198.shtml|title=Napoli, Sarri: \"Sono cose che succedono in campo\"|publisher=}}</ref> Sarri was consequently fined \u20ac20,000 and banned for two Coppa Italia matches by [[Lega Serie A]] for \"directing extremely insulting epithets at the coach of the opposing team\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/78710/two-game-ban-sarri|title=Two-game ban for Sarri - Football Italia|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMancini is married to Federica, although reports in 2015 had stated they had been in the processes of separating.<ref name=kids>{{cite web|url=https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Serie-A/Inter/26-06-2015/inter-mancini-si-separa-moglie-federica-120319067042.shtml|title=Roberto Mancini's announcement: \"I separate myself from my wife Federica\"|publisher=gazzetta.it|date=26 June 2015|language=Italian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/fa-cup-special-the-roberto-mancini-860627|title=FA Cup special: The Roberto Mancini story|publisher=manchestereveningnews.co.uk|date=13 May 2011}}</ref> The couple have a daughter and two sons, [[Filippo Mancini|Filippo]] and [[Andrea Mancini|Andrea]],<ref name=kids/> who have both played in the [[F.C. Internazionale Milano Primavera|Inter youth]] ranks, where Filippo has played ten minutes in a Coppa Italia match. Both of his sons have at one point been a part of [[Manchester City F.C. Reserves and Academy|Manchester City's under-21 youth team]]. Filippo trained with the club's youth/reserve team for several months during the 2007\u201308 season before Roberto was appointed as City's manager, while Andrea was signed by his father for the [[Manchester City F.C. Reserves and Academy#Elite Development Squad|Elite Development Squad]] in November 2010 after being released from [[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]]. [[Andrea Mancini|Andrea]] was released at the end of the [[2011\u201312 Premier League|2011\u201312]] season.\n\nMancini was estimated to have a personal wealth of \u00a319 million in 2011.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Manchester City's Sheikh Mansour leads football's rich list with \u00a320bn |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/oct/05/manchester-city-sheikh-mansour-rich-list?newsfeed=true |newspaper=The Guardian |date=5 October 2011 |accessdate=2011-10-05 |location=London}}</ref> Mancini has joked about watching the soap opera ''[[Coronation Street]]'' to help improve his English.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/manchester-city/8044549/Manchester-City-manager-Roberto-Mancinis-spat-with-Carlos-Tevez-adds-to-soap-opera.html|title=Manchester City manager Roberto Mancini's spat with Carlos T\u00e9vez adds to soap opera|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=6 October 2010|accessdate=26 November 2015}}</ref> Mancini has maintained a tradition of wearing a scarf of his club's colours.<ref>{{cite web|author=England |url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/9/england/2010/01/03/1723180/manchester-city-run-out-of-roberto-mancini-scarves |title=Manchester City Run Out of Roberto Mancini Scarves |publisher=Goal.com |date=3 January 2010 |accessdate=2010-04-27}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Player===\n\n====Club====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club<ref>{{Cite news|title=Roberto Mancini's player statistics|url=https://www.thefinalball.com/jogador.php?id=29794|publisher=Footballzz|date=23 June 2012 |accessdate=2012-06-23}}</ref>\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!colspan=\"2\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup<ref group=\"nb\">Includes [[Supercoppa Italiana]]</ref>\n!colspan=\"2\"|[[UEFA|Europe]]<ref group=\"nb\">Includes [[UEFA Champions League]], [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]], [[UEFA Cup Winners' Cup|Winners' Cup]]</ref>\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n|-\n|[[Bologna F.C. 1909|Bologna]]\n|[[1981\u201382 Serie A|1981\u201382]]\n|30||9||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||31||9\n|-\n|rowspan=\"16\"|[[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]]\n|[[1982\u201383 Serie A|1982\u201383]]\n|22||4||5||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||27||5\n|-\n|[[1983\u201384 Serie A|1983\u201384]]\n|30||8||8||2||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||38||10\n|-\n|[[1984\u201385 Serie A|1984\u201385]]\n|24||3||11||3||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||35||6\n|-\n|[[1985\u201386 Serie A|1985\u201386]]\n|23||6||11||4||4||2||38||12\n|-\n|[[1986\u201387 Serie A|1986\u201387]]\n|26||6||5||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||31||6\n|-\n|[[1987\u201388 Serie A|1987\u201388]]\n|30||5||13||3||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||43||8\n|-\n|[[1988\u201389 Serie A|1988\u201389]]\n|29||9||11||5||8||0||48||14\n|-\n|[[1989\u201390 Serie A|1989\u201390]]\n|31||11||4||2||9||2||44||15\n|-\n|[[1990\u201391 Serie A|1990\u201391]]\n|30||12||10||2||7||2||47||16\n|-\n|[[1991\u201392 Serie A|1991\u201392]]\n|29||6||7||3||9||4||45||13\n|-\n|[[1992\u201393 Serie A|1992\u201393]]\n|30||15||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||32||15\n|-\n|[[1993\u201394 Serie A|1993\u201394]]\n|30||12||7||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||37||12\n|-\n|[[1994\u201395 Serie A|1994\u201395]]\n|31||9||3||1||4||2||38||12\n|-\n|[[1995\u201396 Serie A|1995\u201396]]\n|26||11||2||1||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||28||12\n|-\n|[[1996\u201397 Serie A|1996\u201397]]\n|33||15||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||35||15\n|-\n!Total\n!424!!132!!101!!27!!19!!12!!566!!168\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]]\n|[[1997\u201398 Serie A|1997\u201398]]\n|34||5||8||1||10||3||52||9\n|-\n|[[1998\u201399 Serie A|1998\u201399]]\n|33||10||7||2||7||0||47||12\n|-\n|[[1999\u20132000 Serie A|1999\u20132000]]\n|20||0||7||3||10||0||37||3\n|-\n!Total\n!87!!15!!22!!6!!27!!3!!136!!24\n|-\n|[[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]]\n|[[2000\u201301 FA Premier League|2000\u201301]]\n|4||0||1||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||5||0\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Career total\n!545!!156!!125!!33!!46!!15!!738!!201 <!--Serie A stats only-->\n|}\n\n====International====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|colspan=\"3\"|[[Italy national football team|Italy national team]]<ref>{{NFT|14131|name=Roberto Mancini|accessdate=2012-06-23}}</ref>\n|-\n!Year!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|1984||2||0\n|-\n|1986||1||0\n|-\n|1987||6||0\n|-\n|1988||9||1\n|-\n|1989||1||0\n|-\n|1990||3||0\n|-\n|1991||6||0\n|-\n|1992||1||0\n|-\n|1993||6||3\n|-\n|1994||1||0\n|-\n!Total||36||4\n|}\n\n====International goals====\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Goal !! Date !! Venue !! Opponent !! Score !! Result !! Competition\n|-\n| 1.\n| June 12, 1988\n| [[Rheinstadion]], [[D\u00fcsseldorf]], [[West Germany]]\n| {{fb|GER}}\n| style=\"text-align:center| 1\u20130\n| style=\"text-align:center| 1\u20131\n| [[UEFA Euro 1988]]\n|-\n| 2.\n|rowspan=\"2\"| March 24, 1993\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[Stadio Renzo Barbera]], [[Palermo]], Italy\n|rowspan=\"2\"| {{fb|MLT}}\n| style=\"text-align:center| 4\u20130\n|rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center| 6\